 {{sort|Reynolds|Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]]}}\n| type        = Relief\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade (roundel in lunette on second storey)\n| artist      = {{sortname|Henry Hugh|Armstead}} or [[John Birnie Philip]]\n| architect   =\n| notes       =\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = The Foreign Office - Downing Street Entrance - geograph.org.uk - 1186804.jpg\n| subject     = {{sortname|Edward Grey, 1st Viscount Grey of|Fallodon}}\n| type        = Relief\n| location    = North fa\u00e7ade\n| date        = 1937\n| artist      = {{sortname|William Reid|Dick}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Edwin|Lutyens}}\n| notes       = <ref>{{Harvnb|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=266}} and {{Harvnb|Smith|2015}}, ''passim''</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Old War Office Building==\n{{Main|Old War Office Building}}\n\n{{Public art header|show_architect=yes|show_material=no|show_dimensions=no|show_owner=no}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Old War Office, Whitehall, London 02.jpg\n| subject     = ''Sorrow of Peace'' and ''Winged Messenger of Peace''\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade\n| date        = \n| artist      = {{sortname|Alfred|Drury}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|William|Young|dab=architect}} and Clyde Young\n| type        =\n| designation =\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=239}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       =\n| subject     = ''Horrors of War'' and ''Dignity of War''\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade\n| date        = \n| artist      = {{sortname|Alfred|Drury}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|William|Young|dab=architect}} and Clyde Young\n| type        =\n| designation =\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=239}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       =\n| subject     = ''Truth'' and ''Justice''\n| location    = Whitehall Place fa\u00e7ade\n| date        =\n| artist      = {{sortname|Alfred|Drury}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|William|Young|dab=architect}} and Clyde Young\n| type        =\n| designation =\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=239}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       =\n| subject     = ''Victory'' and ''Fame''\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Avenue]] fa\u00e7ade\n| date        = \n| artist      = {{sortname|Alfred|Drury}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|William|Young|dab=architect}} and Clyde Young\n| type        =\n| designation =\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=239}}\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Equestrian statue of Charles I, Charing Cross]], which faces down Whitehall\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Blackwood\n | first = John\n | year = 1989\n | title = London's Immortals: The Complete Outdoor Commemorative Statues\n | publisher = Savoy Press\n | location    = London and Oxford\n | ISBN = 978-0951429600\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last1 = Bradley | first1 = Simon\n | last2 = Pevsner |first2 = Nikolaus\n | year = 2003\n | title = London 6: Westminster\n | series = The Buildings of England\n | location    = London and New Haven\n | publisher = Yale University Press\n | ISBN = 978-0-300-09595-1\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Gleichen\n | first = Lord Edward\n | year = 1973\n | title = London's Open-Air Statuary\n | location = Bath\n | publisher = Cedric Chivers Ltd\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | title = Walks through London\n | volume = 1\n | last = Hughson | first = David\n | date        = 1817\n | location    = London\n | publisher = Sherwood, Neely & Jones\n}}\n\n* {{Citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Kershman | first = Andrew\n | year = 2013\n | title = London's Monuments\n | location    = London\n | publisher = Metro Publications\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Matthews | first = Peter\n | year = 2018\n | title = London's Statues and Monuments\n | location = Oxford\n | publisher = Shire Publications\n | ISBN = 978-1-78442-256-1\n}}\n\n* {{Citation\n | last = Smith | first = Richard\n | year = 2015\n | title = A Fitting Tribute: The debate over the memorial to Viscount Grey of Fallodon\n | location    = London\n | publisher = Foreign & Commonwealth Office\n | URL = https://issuu.com/fcohistorians/docs/fco896_gray_memorial_booklet_-_web_812e11dc3c95ff\n | accessdate = 30 March 2018\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | last = Ward-Jackson | first = Philip\n | year = 2011\n | title = Public Sculpture of Historic Westminster: Volume 1\n | series = Public Sculpture of Britain\n | volume = 14\n | location    = Liverpool\n | publisher = Liverpool University Press\n | ISBN = 978-1-84631-691-3\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n |url         = https://www.westminster.gov.uk/sites/default/files/uploads/workspace/assets/publications/S-and-M-FINAL-VERSION-1243433604.pdf\n |author      = Westminster City Council\n |title       = Statues and Monuments in Westminster: Guidance for the Erection of New Monuments Supplementary Planning Document\n |accessdate  = 7 July 2018\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Public art in London}}\n{{Portal bar|Lists|London|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of public art in the City of Westminster|Whitehall]]\n[[Category:Whitehall|*Public art]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\nThis is a '''list of public art in [[Whitehall]]''', a district in the [[City of Westminster]], [[London]].\n\nWhitehall is at the centre of the highest concentration of memorials in the City of Westminster, in which 47% of the total number of such works in the borough are located.<ref>{{Harvnb|Westminster City Council|p=10}}</ref> It includes the eponymous street of Whitehall and [[Horse Guards Parade]], both important ceremonial spaces, and [[Horse Guards Road]], which forms its western boundary with [[St James's Park]]. The area's monuments are mainly military in character, foremost among them being the [[The Cenotaph|Cenotaph]], which is the focal point of the [[Remembrance Sunday#National ceremony in the United Kingdom|national Remembrance Sunday commemorations]] held each year.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.britishlegion.org.uk/remembrance/how-the-nation-remembers/memorials |title=Memorials |publisher=The Royal British Legion |accessdate=8 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131034727/http://www.britishlegion.org.uk/remembrance/how-the-nation-remembers/memorials |archivedate=31 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n{{Public art header|show_architect=yes|show_material=no|show_dimensions=no|show_owner=no}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Charles 1er Banqueting House Londres.jpg\n| commonscat  = Bust of Charles I, Banqueting House, London\n| subject     = {{sort|Charles 1|Bust of [[Charles I of England|Charles&nbsp;I]]}}\n| location    = [[Banqueting House, Whitehall|Banqueting House]]\n| date        = {{circa|1800|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = Anon.\n| architect   =\n| type        = Bust\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1357353 Grade I]}}\n| notes       = One of three busts of Charles I found in a builder's yard in [[Fulham]] by [[Hedley Hope-Nicholson]], Secretary of the [[Society of King Charles the Martyr]], in 1945.{{sfn|Matthews|2018|p=20}} Installed here in 1950.{{sfn|Kershman|2013|p=39}} The plaque below is inscribed <small>HIS MAJESTY KING CHARLES I/ PASSED THROUGH THIS HALL AND/ OUT OF A WINDOW NEARLY OVER/ THIS TABLET TO THE SCAFFOLD/ IN WHITEHALL WHERE HE WAS/ BEHEADED ON 20TH JANUARY 1649</small>.\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = C\u00e1diz Memorial, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|C\u00e1diz|[[C\u00e1diz Memorial|Memorial]] to the [[Siege&nbsp;of&nbsp;C\u00e1diz]]}}\n| commonscat  = C\u00e1diz Memorial, London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5042|-0.1273|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1814 (base)\n| artist      = {{sortname|Robert|Shipster|nolink=yes}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| type        = Memorial\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1357126 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 12 August 1816.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hughson|1817|pages=224\u20136}}</ref> A French mortar from the siege, presented by Spain in thanks for Wellington's lifting of the siege. The mortar is mounted on a figure of the mythological monster [[Geryon]] and (at the back) his two-headed dog [[Orthrus]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.alastorrarebooks.com/files/cat-24-running-pages.pdf|title=Catalogue Twenty Four|publisher=Alastor Rare Books|page=4|date=2013|location=Lymington|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208114527/http://www.alastorrarebooks.com/files/cat-24-running-pages.pdf|archivedate=8 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The support was made by the Carriage Department of the [[Royal Arsenal]] to Shipster's design.{{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=256}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Red Lion, Parliament St, London (3rd floor details).jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Dicken|Bust of [[Charles&nbsp;Dickens]]}}\n| location    = The [[Red Lion, Westminster|Red Lion]], Parliament Street\n| date        = 1900\n| artist      = Anon.\n| architect   = Gardiner & Theobald\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1226437 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Commemorates an occasion in Dickens's boyhood when he visited this pub and asked for a glass of \"genuine stunning\" ale; he was given one, as well as a kiss, by the landlady.{{sfn|Gleichen|1973|p=136}}{{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=246}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Duke of Cambridge statue Whitehall.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Cambridge|[[Equestrian statue of the Duke of Cambridge, Whitehall|Statue]]&nbsp;of [[Prince&nbsp;George, Duke&nbsp;of&nbsp;Cambridge]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Prince George, Duke of Cambridge, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]], opposite the [[War Office|Old War Office Building]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.505243|-0.126614|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1907\n| artist      = {{sortname|Adrian|Jones|dab=sculptor}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|John|Belcher|dab=architect}}\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066108 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 15 June 1907.{{sfn|Ward-Jackson|2011|p=413}} Jones was appointed a Member of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] for this work.<ref>{{citation|first=Sarah |last=Crellin|title=Jones, Adrian (1845\u20131938) |work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2004 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/34220 |accessdate=6 January 2013 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In 2012 the sword was broken off by a man who had stripped naked and mounted the statue in what was described as a \"psychotic episode\".<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/9703491/Naked-man-who-climbed-statue-of-Duke-of-Cambridge-had-psychotic-episode.html |title=Naked man who climbed statue of Duke of Cambridge had 'psychotic episode' |work=The Telegraph |date=26 November 2012 |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = King Charles Street closed entry - panoramio.jpg\n| commonscat  = King Charles Street Archway, London\n| subject     = Archway\n| location    = King Charles Street\n| date        = 1908\n| artist      = {{sortname|Paul Raphael|Montford}} and [[William Silver Frith]]\n| architect   = {{sortname|John|Brydon|nolink=yes}} and [[Henry Tanner (architect)|Henry Tanner]]\n| type        =\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066103 Grade II*]}}\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=270}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of the Duke of Devonshire in Whitehall (cropped).jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Devonshire|[[Statue of the Duke of Devonshire, Whitehall|Statue]] of [[Spencer&nbsp;Cavendish, 8th&nbsp;Duke&nbsp;of Devonshire]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Spencer Cavendish, 8th Duke of Devonshire, Whitehall, London\n| location    = Junction of [[Horse Guards Avenue]] and [[Whitehall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5048|-0.1262|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1909\u20131910\n| artist      = {{sortname|Herbert|Hampton}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Howard|Ince|nolink=yes}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1224271 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 14 February 1911. The statue of the Duke in his Garter robes stands on a pedestal of [[Darley Dale]] stone. Edward VII, as a close friend of the Duke, took a personal interest in the memorial, asking Hampton to bring the ''[[modello]]'' to Buckingham Palace for his inspection.<ref>{{Harvnb|Blackwood|1989|p=212}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of Robert Clive, King Charles Street, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Clive|[[Statue of Robert Clive, London|Statue]] of [[Robert&nbsp;Clive, 1st&nbsp;Baron Clive]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Clive of India, London\n| location    = King Charles Street, facing [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.502311|-0.129242|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1912\n| artist      = {{sortname|John|Tweed}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|George Somers|Clarke|link=Somers Clarke}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1221431 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Erected 1912 in the gardens of [[Gwydyr House]]; moved to present site in 1916. The statue was the brainchild of [[George Curzon, 1st Marquess Curzon of Kedleston|Lord Curzon]], who felt that Clive had been insufficiently honoured for his role in establishing the British Empire in India. A marble version was also created for erection in Calcutta.{{sfn|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=108\u201311}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = S F-E-CAMERON LONDON CENOTAPH.JPG\n| subject     = {{sort|Cenotaph|[[The Cenotaph|Cenotaph]]}}\n| commonscat  = Cenotaph, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.502711|-0.126107|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1920\n| artist      = {{sortname|Francis Derwent|Wood}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Edwin|Lutyens}}\n| type        = Memorial\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1357354 Grade I]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 11 November ([[Armistice Day]]) 1920 by [[George V]]. Lutyens's temporary cenotaph in wood and plaster, designed and built in two weeks in July 1919, proved so popular that this permanent version of the same design was erected the following year. It commemorates the dead of both world wars.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/cenoptaph.html |title=The Cenotaph |publisher=Veterans UK |accessdate=23 January 2015 |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140805133045/http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/cenoptaph.html |archivedate=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of Viscount Wolseley, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Wolseley|[[Equestrian statue of the Viscount Wolseley|Statue]] of [[Garnet&nbsp;Wolseley, 1st&nbsp;Viscount&nbsp;Wolseley]]}}\n| commonscat  = Equestrian statue of the Viscount Wolseley\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5050|-0.1275|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1920\n| artist      = {{sortname|William Goscombe|John|link=Goscombe John}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Richard|Allison|dab=architect}}\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1357125 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 25 June 1920 by the [[Prince Arthur of Connaught|Duke of Connaught]]. Goscombe John was awarded this commission on the strength of his equestrian bronze of [[Godfrey Morgan, 1st Viscount Tredegar|Lord Tredegar]] in [[Cathays Park]], Cardiff. Trafalgar Square was initially considered as the location for this statue. It was stored for safekeeping at [[Berkhamsted Castle]], Hertfordshire, between 1941 and 1949.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=67\u20138}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of the Earl Roberts, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Roberts|[[Equestrian statue of the Earl Roberts, London|Statue]] of [[Frederick&nbsp;Roberts, 1st&nbsp;Earl&nbsp;Roberts]]}}\n| commonscat  = Equestrian statue of the Earl Roberts in Horse Guards Parade, London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5045|-0.1274|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1924\n| artist      = {{sortname|Henry|Poole|dab=sculptor}} <small>after [[Harry Bates (sculptor)|Harry Bates]]</small>\n| architect   = {{sortname|Richard|Allison|dab=architect}}\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1231292 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 30 May 1924 by the [[Prince Arthur of Connaught|Duke of Connaught]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=68\u201370}}</ref> A scaled-down replica of Bates's 30-foot high bronze of Lord Roberts, erected in Calcutta in 1896. Another, earlier replica by Poole is in [[Kelvingrove Park]], Glasgow.<ref>{{citation|url=http://193.132.104.136/index.php?title=Bates,_Harry_(1850-1899),_Sculptor |title=Bates, Harry (1850\u20131899), Sculptor |work=Your Archives |publisher=The National Archives |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20111204143126/http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Bates,_Harry_(1850-1899),_Sculptor |archivedate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = London, UK (August 2014) - 147.JPG\n| subject     = [[Royal Naval Division War&nbsp;Memorial]]\n| commonscat  = Royal Naval Division Memorial\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5054|-0.1290|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1925\n| artist      = {{sortname|Eric|Broadbent|nolink=yes}} <small>and F. J. Wilcoxson</small>\n| architect   = {{sortname|Edwin|Lutyens}}\n| type        = Fountain with obelisk\n| designation = {{sort|B|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1392454 Grade II*]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 25 April 1925 by [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=\"EH RND memorial\">{{NHLE|num=1392454|desc=Royal Naval Division War Memorial|fewer-links=x|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref> Inscribed with words from the poem \"1914. III. The Dead\" by [[Rupert Brooke]], who served in the RND.<ref>{{citation |url=http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Royal_Naval_Division_Memorial |title=Royal Naval Division Memorial |work=Your Archives |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref> Put into storage 1939, re-erected outside the [[Old Royal Naval College]] at Greenwich in 1959, and returned to its original site in 2003.<ref name=\"EH RND memorial\"/>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of the Earl Kitchener, London - closeup.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Kitchener|[[Statue of the Earl Kitchener, London|Statue]] of [[Herbert&nbsp;Kitchener, 1st&nbsp;Earl&nbsp;Kitchener]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener, London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5039|-0.1280|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1926\n| artist      = {{sortname|John|Tweed}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1231295 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 9 June 1926 by the [[Edward VIII|Prince of Wales]].<ref name=\"PW-J Kitchener\">{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=72\u20134}}</ref> Set against a stone screen abutting the garden wall of [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1231295|desc=Statue of Lord Kitchener|accessdate=21 November 2013|fewer-links=x}}</ref> A larger national memorial to Kitchener, the tomb designed by [[William Reid Dick]], had been erected in [[St Paul's Cathedral]] the previous year.<ref name=\"PW-J Kitchener\"/>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Guards Division War Memorial.jpg\n| subject     = [[Guards Memorial|Guards Division War&nbsp;Memorial]]\n| commonscat  = Guards Memorial, London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Parade]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.504502|-0.12954|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1926\n| artist      = {{sortname|Gilbert|Ledward}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|H. Chalton|Bradshaw}}\n| type        = Memorial with sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1231315 Grade I]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 16 October 1926. The bronze figures represent five individual soldiers from the Grenadier, Coldstream, [[Scots Guards|Scots]], [[Irish Guards|Irish]] and [[Welsh Guards]]; they were cast from captured German guns. After it sustained bomb damage in the Blitz, Ledward asked that some of the \"honourable scars of war\" be left on the memorial.<ref>{{citation |url=http://yourarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk/index.php?title=Ledward,_Gilbert_(1888-1960)_Sculptor |title=Ledward, Gilbert (1888\u20131960) Sculptor |work=Your Archives |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Earl Haig Memorial, Whitehall, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Haig|[[Earl Haig Memorial|Statue]] of [[Douglas&nbsp;Haig, 1st&nbsp;Earl&nbsp;Haig]]}}''\n| commonscat  = Earl Haig Memorial, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5043|-0.1263|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1937\n| artist      = {{sortname|Alfred Frank|Hardiman}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Stephen Rowland|Pierce}}\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|B|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066109 Grade II*]}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 10 November 1937. The statue aroused great controversy, comparable even with the reaction to [[Jacob Epstein]]'s early works. The depiction of the horse was deemed to be unnatural; ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'' noted that its legs were in the position for urinating.<ref>{{citation |first=Nicholas |last=Watkins |year=2008 |url=http://www.henry-moore.org/docs/a_kick_in_the_teeth_1.pdf |title=A Kick in the Teeth. The equestrian monument to 'Field Marshal Earl Haig, Commander-in-Chief of the British Armies in France 1915\u20131918' by Alfred Hardiman |publisher=Henry Moore Institute |accessdate=14 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331220915/http://www.henry-moore.org/docs/a_kick_in_the_teeth_1.pdf |archivedate=31 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Earth and Water Statues on MoD Main Building in London MOD 45152995.jpg\n| commonscat  = Earth and Water by Charles Wheeler\n| subject     = ''Earth'' and ''Water''\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Avenue]], outside [[Ministry of Defence Main Building (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence Main Building]]\n| date        = 1949\u20131952\n| artist      = {{sortname|Charles|Wheeler|dab=sculptor}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Vincent|Harris}}\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1278223 Grade I]}}\n| notes       = Carved from 40 tons of [[Portland stone]]. Corresponding sculptures of ''Fire'' and ''Air'' (completing the [[Classical element|four elements]]) were originally intended for the building's southern entrance, but were vetoed by the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]].{{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=243}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = London 074 Dept of Energy 3 Whitehall Place (9185416307).jpg\n| subject     = ''Agriculture''&nbsp;and ''Sea&nbsp;and&nbsp;Fisheries''\n| location    = 3 Whitehall Place\n| date        = {{circa|1952|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = {{sortname|James|Woodford}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|C. E.|Mee|nolink=yes}}\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|B|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066106 Grade II*]}}\n| notes       = <ref>{{citation|url=http://sculpture.gla.ac.uk/view/person.php?id=msib2_1208277486|title=James Arthur Woodford RA, OBE|work=Mapping the Practice and Profession of Sculpture in Briatin & Ireland 1851\u20131951}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Bernard Montgomery Statue, Whitehall, London.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Montgomery|[[Statue of the Viscount Montgomery, London|Statue]] of [[Bernard&nbsp;Montgomery, 1st&nbsp;Viscount Montgomery of&nbsp;Alamein]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Bernard Montgomery, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]], outside the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.503364|-0.125809|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1980\n| artist      = {{sortname|Oscar|Nemon}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 6 June 1980 by the [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Mother]]. The texture of the lower parts of the statue was achieved by mixing old plaster from the studio floor with fresh plaster at the modelling stage. Another cast stands in Brussels,<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=423\u20135}}</ref> at a traffic intersection called [[Montgomery Square]].\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of Lord Mountbatten (29378962570) (cropped).jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Mountbatten|[[Statue of the Earl Mountbatten, London|Statue]] of [[Louis&nbsp;Mountbatten, 1st&nbsp;Earl Mountbatten of&nbsp;Burma]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma\n| location    = Mountbatten Green, off [[Horse Guards Road]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.503607|-0.12866|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1983\n| artist      = {{sortname|Franta|Belsky}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Charles|Pollard|nolink=yes}} <small>(Lettering by [[David Kindersley]])</small>\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 2 November 1983 by [[Elizabeth II]]. The statue stands on a pedestal at the centre of a low stepped pyramid, a scheme much reduced in ambition from Belsky's competition-winning design which included fountains representing the four seas. The financial constraints and \"a very restrictive brief\" resulted in a finished work which dissatisfied the sculptor.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=77\u20139}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Field Marshal The Viscount Slim.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Slim|[[Statue of the Viscount Slim, London|Statue]] of [[William&nbsp;Slim, 1st&nbsp;Viscount Slim]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of William Slim, 1st Viscount Slim, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]], outside the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.503803|-0.125853|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1990\n| artist      = {{sortname|Ivor|Roberts-Jones}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|David|Kindersley}} <small>(lettering)</small>\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 28 April 1990 by [[Elizabeth II]]. Roberts-Jones had fought in the [[Burma Campaign]] of World War II, in which Slim was a commander.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=425\u20136}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of Lord Alanbrooke (8281927746).jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Alanbrooke|[[Statue of the Viscount Alanbrooke, London|Statue]] of [[Alan&nbsp;Brooke, 1st&nbsp;Viscount Alanbrooke]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Alan Brooke, 1st Viscount Alanbrooke, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]], outside the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.503587|-0.125815|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1993 \n| artist      = {{sortname|Ivor|Roberts-Jones}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|David|Kindersley}} <small>(lettering)</small>\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 25 May 1993 by [[Elizabeth II]]. For the installation of this, the last of the statues of Field Marshals on what was formerly called Raleigh Green, the area was re-configured by the landscape architects RMJM and the statue of Sir Walter Raleigh removed to Greenwich.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=426\u20138}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Gurkha Soldier Monument, London - April 2008.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Gurkhas|[[Gurkha Memorial, London|Memorial]] to the [[Brigade&nbsp;of&nbsp;Gurkhas]]}}\n| commonscat  = The Gurkha Soldier, London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Avenue]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.505098|-0.125007|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1997\n| artist      = {{sortname|Philip|Jackson|dab=sculptor}} <small>after [[Richard Reginald Goulden]]</small>\n| architect   = {{sortname|Cecil Denny|Highton|nolink=yes}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 3 December 1997 by [[Elizabeth II]]. Modelled on a 1924 sculpture by Goulden in the Foreign Office. The [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|Hong Kong Handover]] transferred the Gurkhas' headquarters to the United Kingdom, which until that point had no memorial to the brigade.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=66\u20137}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Royal Tank Regiment Memorial, Whitehall Place, London.jpg\n| subject     = [[Royal Tank Regiment Memorial]]\n| commonscat  = Royal Tank Regiment Memorial, Whitehall Place\n| location    = Whitehall Court\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.506129|-0.124442|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 2000\n| artist      = {{sortname|Vivien|Mallock}} <small>after [[George Henry Paulin]]</small>\n| architect   = {{sortname|Christopher|Rainsford|nolink=yes}} <small>for [[HOK (firm)|HOK]] International</small>\n| type        = Sculptural group\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 13 June 2000 by [[Elizabeth II]]. The group depicts the five-man crew of a World War II-era [[Comet tank]]; it is an enlarged version of Paulin's statuette of 1953 in the [[The Tank Museum|Tank Museum]], [[Bovington]], Dorset. Mallock's husband had been an officer in the RTR in the 1960s.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=430\u20132}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = UK-2014-London-Monument to the Women of World War II (1).jpg\n| subject     = [[Monument&nbsp;to the Women&nbsp;of&nbsp;World&nbsp;War&nbsp;II]]\n| commonscat  = Monument to the Women of World War II, Whitehall, London\n| location    = [[Whitehall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5035|-0.1262|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 2005\n| artist      = {{sortname|John W.|Mills}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Giles|Quarme|nolink=yes}}\n| type        = Plinth with reliefs\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 9 July 2005 by [[Elizabeth II]]. Around the plinth are reliefs of servicewomen's clothing and protective costumes, appearing as if they have been hung up at the end of a working day.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|p=428}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Bali bombing memorial in London, Horse Guard Road.JPG\n| subject     = {{sort|Bali|[[Bali Bombings Memorial, London|Memorial]] to&nbsp;the [[2002&nbsp;Bali&nbsp;bombings]]}}\n| commonscat  = Bali Memorial in London\n| location    = [[Horse Guards Road]], rear of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.502410|-0.129572|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 2006\n| artist      = {{sortname|Martin|Cook|nolink=yes}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Gary|Breeze|nolink=yes}}\n| type        = Memorial\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 12 October 2006, the fourth anniversary of the bombings, by the [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince of Wales]] and the [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]]. The memorial consists of a granite globe carved with 202 doves{{em dash}}one for each individual killed in the bombings{{em dash}}and a wall inscribed with their names.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=79\u201380}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Foreign and Commonwealth Office==\n{{Main|Foreign and Commonwealth Office}}\n{{Public art header|show_architect=yes|show_material=no|show_dimensions=no|show_owner=no}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = America Whitehall.jpg\n| subject     = ''America''\n| type        = Relief\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade (spandrel on first storey)\n| artist      = {{sortname|Henry Hugh|Armstead}}\n| architect   =\n| notes       = <ref>{{citation|url=http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/armstead/1.html|title=''America'' by Henry Hugh Armstead (1828\u20131905)|first=Jacqueline|last=Banerjee|work=The Victorian Web|date=12 August 2011|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Australasia Whitehall.jpg\n| subject     = ''Australasia''\n| type        = Relief\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade (spandrel on first storey)\n| artist      = {{sortname|Henry Hugh|Armstead}}\n| architect   =\n| notes       = <ref>{{citation|url=http://www.victorianweb.org/sculpture/armstead/2.html|title=''Australasia'' by Henry Hugh Armstead|first=Jacqueline|last=Banerjee|work=The Victorian Web|date=6 June 2011|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Africa Whitehall.jpg\n| subject     = ''Africa''\n| type        = Relief\n| location    = Whitehall fa\u00e7ade (spandrel on first storey)\n| ar