\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Japanese Story]]''\n| 2003\n| Sandy Edwards\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Last Shot]]''\n| 2004\n| Emily French\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Connie and Carla]]''\n| 2004\n| Carla\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[In Her Shoes (film)|In Her Shoes]]''\n| 2005\n| Rose Feller\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]''\n| 2006\n| Sheryl Hoover\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Night Listener (film)|The Night Listener]]''\n| 2006\n| Donna D. Logand\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Like Minds]]''\n| 2006\n| Sally Rowe\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Dead Girl]]''\n| 2006\n| Arden\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Evening (film)|Evening]]''\n| 2007\n| Nina Mars\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Towelhead (film)|Towelhead]]''\n| 2007\n| Melina Hines\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Black Balloon (film)|The Black Balloon]]''\n| 2008\n| Maggie Mollison\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hey, Hey, It's Esther Blueburger]]''\n| 2008\n| Mary\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mary and Max]]''\n| 2009\n| Mary Daisy Dinkle\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Jesus Henry Christ]]''\n| 2011\n| Patricia Herman\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fright Night (2011 film)|Fright Night]]''\n| 2011\n| Jane Brewster\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Foster (film)|Foster]]''\n| 2011\n| Zooey\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]]''\n| 2012\n| [[Peggy Robertson]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mental (2012 film)|Mental]]''\n| 2012\n| Sharon \"Shaz\" Thornbender\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Way, Way Back]]''\n| 2013\n| Pam\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Enough Said]]''\n| 2013\n| Sarah\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[Lucky Them]]''\n| 2013\n| Ellie Klug\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[A Long Way Down (film)|A Long Way Down]]''\n| 2014\n| Maureen Thompson\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[Tammy (film)|Tammy]]''\n| 2014\n| Missi Jenkins\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hector and the Search for Happiness (film)|Hector and the Search for Happiness]]''\n| 2014\n| Agnes\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Boxtrolls]]''\n| 2014\n| Lady Portley Rind\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Glassland]]''\n| 2014\n| Jean\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Blinky Bill the Movie]]''\n| 2015\n| Beryl and Cheryl\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Miss You Already]]''\n| 2015\n| Milly\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Krampus (film)|Krampus]]''\n| 2015\n| Sarah Engel\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Imperium (2016 film)|Imperium]]''\n| 2016\n| Angela Zamparo\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Jasper Jones (film)|Jasper Jones]]''\n| 2017\n| Ruth Bucktin\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[XXX: Return of Xander Cage]]''\n| 2017\n| Jane Marke\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Yellow Birds (film)|The Yellow Birds]]''\n| 2017\n| Amy Bartle\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fun Mom Dinner]]''\n| 2017\n| Kate\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Unlocked (2017 film)|Unlocked]]''\n| 2017\n| Emily Knowles\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Madame (2017 film)|Madame]]''\n| 2017\n| Anne Fredericks\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Please Stand By]]''\n| 2017\n| Scottie\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]''\n| 2018\n| Annie Graham\n| Also executive producer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hearts Beat Loud]]''\n| 2018\n| Leslie\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Birthmarked (film)|Birthmarked]]''\n| 2018\n| Catherine\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Velvet Buzzsaw]]''\n| 2019\n| Gretchen\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Knives Out]]''\n| 2019\n| Joni Thrombey\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dream Horse (film)|Dream Horse]]''\n| 2020\n| Jan Vokes\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Stowaway (upcoming film)|Stowaway]]''\n| 2020\n| \n| Post-production\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[I'm Thinking of Ending Things (film)|I'm Thinking of Ending Things]]''\n| TBA\n|\n| Post-production\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nightmare Alley (upcoming film)|Nightmare Alley]]''\n| TBA\n| Zeena Krumbein\n| Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Years\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[A Country Practice]]''\n| 1990\n| Tracy\n| Episode: \"The Sting: Part 1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Dinner with Friends]]''\n| 2001\n| Beth\n| Television movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Tsunami: The Aftermath]]''\n| 2006\n| Kathy Graham\n| Television movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[United States of Tara]]''\n| 2009\u20132011\n| Tara Gregson\n| 36 episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Rake (Australian TV series)|Rake]]''\n| 2012\n| Claudia Marshall, Premier of New South Wales\n| Episode: \"R vs Mohammed\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]''\n| 2013\u20132014\n| Ellen Sanders\n| 15 episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Devil's Playground (TV series)|Devil's Playground]]''\n| 2014\n| Margaret Wallace\n| Episode: \"I Will Bring Fire onto This Earth\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Wanderlust (UK TV series)|Wanderlust]]''\n| 2018\n| Joy Richards\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]''\n| 2019\n| Det. Grace Rasmussen\n| Miniseries\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Pieces of Her (TV series)|Pieces of Her]]''\n| 2020\n| Laura Oliver<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/pieces-of-her-toni-collette-star-netflix-thriller-series-minkie-spiro-direct-1202848386/|title=Toni Collette To Star In 'Pieces Of Her' Netflix Drama Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=February 3, 2020|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|Main role\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'' (2006) \u2013 Toni Collette & the Finish\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n[[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|commons=Category:Toni Collette|d=Q229291|b=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|species=no|m=no|mw=no|n=no|q=no|wikt=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0001057}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/toni-collette Toni Collette at Emmys.com]\n\n{{navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette|Awards for Toni Collette]]\n|list =\n{{AACTA Award Best Actress in a Leading Role 2000\u20132019}}\n{{AACTAAward BestSupportingActress 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Miniseries Supporting Actress}}\n{{EmmyAward ComedyLeadActress 2001\u20132025}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActressTVComedy 1990\u20132009}}\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actress}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collette, Toni}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Australian female singers]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Institute of Dramatic Art alumni]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress AACTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress AACTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Theatre World Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian actress and musician}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Toni Collette\n| image              = Toni Collette 2013.jpg\n| caption            = Collette in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1972|11|1}}\n| birth_name         = Toni Collett<!-- Collett is her birth name, she added the e for her stage name -->\n| birth_place        = [[Plumpton, New South Wales]], Australia\n| alma_mater         = [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]<br/>[[Australian Theatre for Young People]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|musician}}\n| years_active       = 1990\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Dave Galafassi|2003}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette|Full List]]\n}}\n'''Toni Collett'''<!-- Her name is not Antonia. In 2015, she said: \"Wikipedia also claims my real name is Antonia, which is absolutely not true.\" --> (born 1 November 1972), credited professionally as '''Toni Collette''',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/07/20/1090089151504.html|title=Free spirit|date=21 July 2004|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.out.com/movies/2015/10/26/toni-collette-talks-skinny-dipping-gay-fandom|title=Toni, Collected|first=R. Kurt|last=Osenlund|date=26 October 2015|journal=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]}}</ref> is an Australian actress and musician. She is particularly known for her work in [[independent films]] as well as supporting roles in studio films. She has received [[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette|numerous accolades]], including a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] and a [[Primetime Emmy Award]], in addition to nominations for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] and a [[Tony Award]].\n\nBorn in [[Sydney]], she is the oldest of three children. Her interest in acting sparked after performing in a high school production of&nbsp;''[[Godspell]]''. She subsequently attended the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] for 18 months before dropping out to take part in a stage production of ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''. She also appeared in stage productions at the Belvoir Street Theatre, under the directorship of [[Geoffrey Rush]]. She made her feature film debut in 1992 and made her breakthrough with the comedy-drama film&nbsp;''[[Muriel's Wedding]]'' (1994), for which she earned a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award]] nomination. She subsequently achieved international recognition for her role&nbsp;in ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999), which became the [[List of highest-grossing horror films|highest grossing horror movie]] at the time and for which she was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]].\n\nCollette subsequently took on roles in several films, such as the period-drama [[The Hours (film)|''The Hours'']] (2002), the drama ''[[Japanese Story]]'' (2003), the comedy-dramas ''[[The Way, Way Back]], [[Enough Said]] and [[Lucky Them]]'' (all 2013), the horror-drama ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]'' (2017) and the mystery ''[[Knives Out (film)|Knives Out]]'' (2019). She received a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] nomination for her role in ''[[About a Boy (film)|About a Boy]]'' (2002) and had a starring role in ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'' (2006). Her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] performances include lead roles in ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'' (2000) and ''[[The Realistic Joneses]]'' (2014), the former of which earned her a nomination for the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical]]. On television, she has played lead roles in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy series ''[[United States of Tara]]'' (2008\u20132011) and the [[Netflix]] miniseries ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]'' (2019). For the former, she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award]].\n\nIn addition to acting, Colette has her own production company, Vocab Films and is the lead singer of the band [[Toni Collette & the Finish]]. In 2006, the band released their debut album ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'', which contained eleven tracks, all of which were written and composed by Collette. She is married to actor and drummer Dave Galafassi with whom she has two children.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Nida dusk.jpg|alt=|thumb|Collette studied acting at the National Institute of Dramatic Art (NIDA) in [[Kensington, New South Wales]]]]\nToni Collett was born in [[Plumpton, New South Wales|Plumpton]], a suburb in [[Sydney]]. Her father, Bob Collett was a truck driver while her mother was a customer-service representative for a courier company.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=She Expanded Her Home to House Her Financial Enterprises|pages=437\u2013456|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press, Inc.|isbn=978-1-5128-1759-1|doi=10.2307/j.ctv5qdjzk.19|title=The Dear-Bought Heritage|year=2015}}</ref> Collett's father was conceived as a result of an affair his mother had with an [[Chief petty officer (United States)|American Chief Petty Officer]] in the U.S. Navy stationed in Australia during [[World War II]]. Despite a public appeal, Collett has not discovered who her biological grandfather was.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityfox.com/stories/man-reunites-with-birth-mother-51-years-after-she-held-him-for-six-hours/|title=Man reunites with birth mother 51 years after she held him for just six hours|last=Wiltons|first=Rebbekah|date=2019-04-04|website=University Fox|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> She has described her family as, \"[not] the most communicative\" but that despite her parents' lack of money, they always made them feel cared for and that they were a supportive family.<ref name=\"McLean\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/apr/26/artsfeatures|title=Interview: Toni Collette|last=McLean|first=Gareth|date=2002-04-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/straight-to-the-top-20030927-gdhgvf.html|title=Straight to the top|date=2003-09-27|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> She has fond memories of growing up in [[Blacktown]] where she and her mother would spend every Saturday afternoon watching a [[Bill Collins (television presenter)|Bill Collins]] movie matinee.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/dont-call-her-muriel-20120903-2593l.html|title=Don't call her Muriel|date=2012-09-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\nShe described her younger self as having \u201ccrazy\u201d amounts of confidence.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jun/10/toni-collette-hereditary-interview-i-dont-like-horror-films|title=Toni Collette: 'I don't like horror films \u2013 I'm too petrified'|last=Ellen|first=Barbara|date=2018-06-10|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-01-05|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> When she was 11, she feigned [[appendicitis]] so successfully that even the doctors were convinced, rushing her to the emergency room and removing her appendix.<ref name=\":2\" /> She attended [[Blacktown Girls High School]] where her early hobbies included playing netball, tap-dancing and swimming.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/10681592/Toni-Collette-interview-If-I-couldnt-work-Id-wither-and-die.html|title=Toni Collette interview: 'If I couldn't work, I'd wither and die'|last=Harrod|first=Horatia|date=2014-03-13|access-date=2020-01-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> She would often take part in singing in local talent competitions as well.<ref name=\":1\"/> Her earliest ambitions were to perform in [[Musical theatre|musicals]] as she loved to sing and dance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/15f94540-7a09-11e6-97ae-647294649b28|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\nHer first acting role was onstage in the musical ''[[Godspell]]'' at 14 years old. She won the role over several other prospective candidates after singing [[Whitney Houston|Whitney Houston's]] \"[[Saving All My Love for You|Saving All My Love For You]]\".<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/actor/toni-collette|title=Toni Collette|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref> She decided to become an actor when she was 15 years old.<ref name=\"McLean\"/> She was deeply influenced by seeing [[Geoffrey Rush]] perform on stage in ''[[The Diary of a Madman]]''. At age 16, with her parents' approval, she left school to pursue a career in acting. She explained her decision to leave school saying, \u201cI was 16. And it\u2019s not like I wasn\u2019t good at school, or I didn\u2019t enjoy it, I did. I just loved acting more. I don\u2019t regret that decision, but I can\u2019t believe I made it\u2026\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> She later attended the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] where she dropped out after 18 months to take a theatre role in director [[Neil Armfield|Neil Armfield's]] stage production of ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Collett added back the extra \"e\" in her surname, which her grandfather had removed, as she felt it sounded better as a stage name.\n\nIn her twenties she found it difficult to adapt to the change of being in the media spotlight and, as a result, struggled with [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] and [[panic attack]]s.<ref name=\":1\" /> During this period she travelled extensively, shaved her head five times and bought a flat in [[Brixton]], [[London]] in order to \"explore different ideas and just look at life and try to understand it.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Acting career==\n=== 1992\u20131998: Breakthrough and early roles ===\nCollette made her television debut in 1990, in a guest appearance on the [[Seven Network]] drama series ''[[A Country Practice]]''. She subsequently joined the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] and performed key roles on stage including Sonya in ''Uncle Vanya'' and [[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]] in ''[[King Lear]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tonicollette.org/information/|title=Information on Toni Collette|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In 1992, she made her feature film debut as part of the ensemble comedy-drama [[Spotswood (film)|''Spotswood'']] (known in the U.S. as ''The Efficiency Expert''), which starred [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Russell Crowe]]. She played Wendy, a factory worker who harbors a secret attraction towards [[Ben Mendelsohn]]'s character. Of her role, Andrew Urban of ''Urban Cinephile'' said that \"Toni Collette has a lovely role and does it with minimalist excellence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=13403&s=DVD|title=Urban Cinefile SPOTSWOOD: DVD|website=www.urbancinefile.com.au|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> For her performance, she earned her first [[AACTA Awards|AACTA Award]] nomination, for [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]]. Between auditions for roles, she worked part-time delivering pizzas and selling jeans.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/toni-collette-some-people-stick-to-the-rules-some-question-them-20180918-p504gh.html|title=Toni Collette: 'Some people stick to the rules, some question them'|last=Kelly|first=Guy|date=2018-09-21|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nDuring her final year at NIDA, her agent informed her of a film that she felt would be a good role for Collette, but had not yet materialized. A year later, Collette's agent apprised her that the project had been financed and that she would be able to audition.<ref>{{Citation|title=Muriel's Wedding 25th Anniversary Celebration Q&A with Toni Collette|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eDw91-owWr8|language=en|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> The project would eventually become ''[[Muriel's Wedding]]''. Although Collette auditioned for the role on the first day of casting, she didn't win it until three months later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/16/arts/up-and-coming-toni-collette-and-rachel-griffiths-muriels-wedding-brings.html|title=UP AND COMING: Toni Collette and Rachel Griffiths; 'Muriel's Wedding' Brings Bliss to Two Young Actresses|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=1995-04-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In order to prepare for the role, Collette gained 42 pounds in 7 weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/let-her-eat-cake-vol-43-no-13/|title=Let Her Eat Cake|website=PEOPLE.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> The film was a critical and commercial success, grossing $57.5 million on a budget of $9 million. [[James Berardinelli]] of ''ReelThoughts'' called her \"vibrant and energetic\", while Peter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' opined that Collette played Muriel with \"disarming earnestness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/muriel-s-wedding|title=Muriel's Wedding|last=Berardinelli|first=James|website=Reelviews Movie Reviews|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Seeking-Bliss-Muriel-Finds-Herself-2990644.php|title=Seeking Bliss, 'Muriel' Finds Herself|last=Stack|first=Peter|date=1996-03-15|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> She received her first [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] nomination, for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress]] and won an [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|AACTA Award for Best Actress]].\n\nIn 1996, she had parts in three critically acclaimed films - the comedy-drama [[Cosi (film)|''Cos\u00ec'']], the period comedy ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]'' and the drama ''[[Lilian's Story]]''. In ''Cos\u00ec'', which reunited her with ''Muriel's Wedding'' castmate [[Rachel Griffiths]], she played an actress recovering from drug addiction. In ''Lillian's Story'' she played an eccentric woman who is sent to a [[Lunatic asylum|mental asylum]] in her youth. [[David Stratton]] of [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']], in a review for the former, said that Collette \"[gave] a terrific performance\", and when reviewing the latter, found her to be \"poignant\" and took note of her range and depth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/cosi-1200445232/|title=Cosi|last=Stratton|first=David|last2=Stratton|first2=David|date=1996-03-26|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/lilian-s-story-1200445381/|title=Lilian's Story|last=Stratton|first=David|last2=Stratton|first2=David|date=1996-03-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> In ''Emma'', an adaptation of the [[Jane Austen]] [[Emma (novel)|novel of the same name]], she played Harriet Smith, a close friend of the [[Emma Woodhouse|titular character]]. Originally dismissive of Austen's works, she found ''Emma'' to be \"warm and witty and clever\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Aussie-actress-shines-in-the-latest-Austen-outing-3131029.php|title=Aussie actress shines in the latest Austen outing|last=Ganahl|first=Jane|last2=Staff|first2=Of the Examiner|date=1996-08-04|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> Jane Ganahl of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said that, \"[Harriet was] played with heartbreaking empathy by Toni Collette\".<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nShe starred alongside [[Lisa Kudrow]], [[Parker Posey]] and [[Alanna Ubach]] in ''[[Clockwatchers]]'' (1997) which depicted the lives of four friends working in an office. Dustin Putman of ''TheFilmFile'' called it a \"jewel of a film\" and praised the performances of the cast, particularly Collette whom he referred to as \"outstanding\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themovieboy.com/reviews/c/97_clockwatchers.htm|title=Dustin Putman's Review: Clockwatchers (1997) - [TheMovieBoy]|website=www.themovieboy.com|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> Her later releases of the 1990s - ''[[8\u00bd Women]]'' and ''[[Velvet Goldmine]]'' were both critically panned and commercial failures. The latter, however, has grown in stature since its release and has become a [[cult film]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encoremag.com/new-york/articles/282/glam-velvet-goldmine-mccarren|title=Glam's Velvet Goldmine Marks End of McCarren's Film Season|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Collette credited ''Velvet Goldmine'' with revitalizing her passion for acting and said that it had freed her from some distress she had been facing that time.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=2833&s=interviews|title=Urban Cinefile COLLETTE, TONI: Sixth Sense|website=www.urbancinefile.com.au|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n=== 1999\u20132004: ''The Sixth Sense,'' Broadway and international recognition ===\nWhen Collette first received the script of ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999), she nearly refrained from reading it, fearing it would be \"some formulaic Hollywood action drama\". However, she found herself moved by the story and agreed to audition, ultimately winning the role over other high-profile actors such as [[Marisa Tomei]]. She was originally ambivalent about receiving the role, as it meant she would be unable to take part in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[Bringing Out the Dead]]'' (1999).<ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/66913/17-straightforward-facts-about-sixth-sense|title=17 Facts about The Sixth Sense|last=|first=|date=|website=www.urbancinefile.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-01-31}}</ref> She played the role of Lynn Sear, a single mother who struggles to raise her son Cole (played by [[Haley Joel Osment]]) who is able to see and speak with ghosts. [[David Edelstein]] said that her performance was \"wonderful\", while John Anderson of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called her \"a revelation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-aug-06-ca-63021-story.html|title=When It Comes to Creepiness, This Project Has a 'Sixth Sense'|date=1999-08-06|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-02-02}}</ref> Journalists took note of Collette's climactic scene, in which Cole reveals his secret to Lynn, as the film's highlight; Gary Thompson of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' said that \"the scene in the car when [Cole] divulges his secret is so riveting... and it\u2019s so well-acted by Osment and Collette\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/movies/sixth-sense-20th-anniversary-m-night-shyamalan-20190727.html|title='The Sixth Sense' at 20: M. Night Shyamalan's breakout still stuns|last=Thompson|first=Gary|website=www.inquirer.com|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:M. Night Shyamalan by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|233x233px|[[M. Night Shyamalan]] cast Collette in ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999) which catapulted her into international fame]]\n''The Sixth Sense'' became an unexpected box-office juggernaut, grossing $670 million on a budget of only $40 million. It became the [[1999 in film|second-highest-grossing film of 1999]], beating several other films such as ''[[The Matrix]]'', ''[[Toy Story 2]]'', and [[American Beauty (1999 film)|''American Beauty'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/how-sixth-sense-conquered-hollywood-1999/595558/|title=How 'The Sixth Sense' Conquered Hollywood in 1999|last=Sims|first=David|date=2019-08-06|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-02-02}}</ref> ''The Sixth Sense'' gathered six [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] which made it the fourth [[Horror film|horror movie]] to be nominated in that category. Collette gained an Oscar nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]. She reflected, \"There was some definite feeling we all had that it was going to somehow be special. And it did actually come to pass that the film did really well and has been loved by a lot of people.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/04/25/hereditary-sixth-sense-toni-collette/|title=Toni Collette says making horror movie 'Hereditary' reminded her of 'The Sixth Sense'\u2014exclusive image|website=EW.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, she made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut with a leading role in [[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|''The Wild Party'']], playing Queenie, a masochistic [[showgirl]] who hosts a lavish party with her husband. The role was originally written for [[Vanessa Williams]] but ultimately went to Collette after Williams became pregnant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talkinbroadway.com/cabaret/lachiusa.html|title=Talkin' Broadway - Cabaret Interview with Michael John LaChiusa|website=www.talkinbroadway.com|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref> [[Charles Isherwood]] felt underwhelmed by the musical and Collette's performance, writing, \"[Collette's] Queenie is flat and one-dimensional; she doesn\u2019t convey the warmth that invites emotional investment\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2000/legit/reviews/the-wild-party-4-1200461750/|title=The Wild Party|last=Isherwood|first=Charles|last2=Isherwood|first2=Charles|date=2000-04-14|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref> [[Ben Brantley]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' was more favourable, stating that, \"Ms. Collette... gives the evening's most fully realized performance\" but criticized her chemistry with [[Yancey Arias]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/14/movies/theater-review-having-fun-yet-jazz-babies.html|title=THEATER REVIEW; Having Fun Yet, Jazz Babies?|last=Brantley|first=Ben|date=2000-04-14|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2020-02-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For this role, Collette was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Leading Actress in a Musical]]. Collette turned down the title role in ''[[Bridget Jones's Diary (film)|Bridget Jones's Diary]]'' because she was committed to perform on Broadway at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/close-casting-calls-toni-collette-in-bridget-joness-diary-2001/|title=Close Casting Calls: Toni Collette In Bridget Jones's Diary (2001)|last=|first=|date=|newspaper=|accessdate=|url-status=live|location=}}</ref>  She followed this with a supporting role in the action thriller [[Shaft (2000 film)|''Shaft'']] (2000). The film received generally positive reviews and grossed $107.2 million on a budget of $46 million. In 2001, her only role was in the [[HBO]] [[Television film|TV movie]] [[Dinner with Friends (film)|''Dinner with Friends'']] (2001). She played Beth, a middle-aged woman who struggles to come to terms with the fact that her husband is leaving her for another woman. Steven Oxman of ''Variety'' said that she was \"well suited\" to her role, while Bruce Fetts of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised her \"flawless\" American accent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/tv/reviews/dinner-with-friends-4-1200469558/|title=Dinner With Friends|last=Oxman|first=Steven|last2=Oxman|first2=Steven|date=2001-08-08|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/08/06/dinner-friends/|title=Dinner With Friends|website=EW.com|language=EN|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref> The show earned a nomination for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie]].\n\nIn 2002, she had supporting roles in two critically acclaimed films. In [[The Hours (film)|''The Hours'']], based on the [[The Hours (novel)|novel of the same name]], she played Kitty, a [[Sexual repression|sexually repressed]] woman who plans to undergo an operation to cure her [[infertility]]. John Patterson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' said that she gave an \"utterly convincing small-scale emotional meltdown born of suburban sadness and sexual self-repression\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reelingreviews.com/thehours.htm|title=The Hours|website=www.reelingreviews.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> The film received positive reviews and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. In [[About a Boy (film)|''About A Boy'']] she played a woman suffering from [[Depression (mood)|depression]] who attempts to commit [[suicide]]. Daniel Saney of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' said that she was \"as impressive as ever\" while Sheila Johnston of ''[[Screen International|Screendaily]]'' priased her \"powerful presence\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/about-a-boy/408661.article|title=About A Boy|last=Johnston2002-03-18T15:29:00+00:00|first=Sheila|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30085/about-a-boy/|title=About A Boy|last=Saney|first=Daniel|date=2006-03-07|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> She was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] for the latter and won the [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for both performances.\n\nCollette played the lead role in ''[[Japanese Story]]'' (2003) as an Australian [[geologist]] who develops an intense relationship with a visiting Japanese businessman. The film was screened at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]]. Her powerful performance led to numerous reviewers welcoming her back to playing lead roles, the first time since ''Muriel's Wedding''. John Patterson wrote that she gave a \"shattering performance, masterfully controlled and detailed, and all the proof her fans ever needed of her special brilliance.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jun/05/patterson.comment|title=On top down under|last=Patterson|first=John|date=2004-06-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Richard Porton of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' remarked, \"Collette's pitch-perfect performance and the stunning evocation of the forbidding and beautiful outback make this film unexpectedly rewarding.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/japanese-story/Film?oid=1151584|title=Japanese Story|last=Porton|first=Richard M.|website=Chicago Reader|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Many critics praised her emotional range, with some regarding the performance to be the best of her career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/j/japanese_story.html|title=Review: Japanese Story|website=preview.reelviews.net|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> Her two releases of 2004 - ''[[The Last Shot]]'' and ''[[Connie and Carla]]'' were both negatively reviewed and box office failures.\n\n===2005\u20132011: Supporting roles and ''United States of Tara''===\nCollette's only film in 2005 was ''[[In Her Shoes (film)|In Her Shoes]]'', a comedy-drama about the relationship between two different sisters and their estranged grandmother, co-starring [[Cameron Diaz]] and [[Shirley MacLaine]]. Based on the 2002 novel [[In Her Shoes (novel)|of the same name]] by [[Jennifer Weiner]], the production received generally positive reviews from critics, and became a moderate independent success, earning a total of US$82.2&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |title=''In Her Shoes'' (2005)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2005/HSHOE.php |publisher=The-Numbers.com|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Collette was subsequently nominated for a [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Satellite Award for Best Actress]] for her performance of a successful-but-lonely lawyer with low self-esteem, which [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' noted the focus of the film: \"As usual, Collette's face is a fine-tuned transmitter of her emotions, moment by moment, and she becomes the locus of audience feeling.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|title=Oh, grow up. And move out of here while you're at it.|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Oh-grow-up-And-move-out-of-here-while-you-re-at-2565906.php|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=7 October 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Collette starred in ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'', a comedy-drama [[road movie]] about a family's trip to a children's beauty pageant. The film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2006, and its distribution rights were bought by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] for one of the biggest deals made in the history of the festival.<ref name=\"RTBiggest\">{{cite web|last=Duong|first=Senh|title=Sundance: Searchlight Spends Big For 'Little Miss Sunshine'|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/news/1646244/sundance-searchlight-spends-big-for-little-miss-sunshine/|accessdate=11 December 2013|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=21 January 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105163935/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/news/1646244/sundance-searchlight-spends-big-for-little-miss-sunshine/|archivedate=5 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sharon Waxaman of ''The New York Times'' called her \"funny and believable\" but Stella Papamichael of [[BBC]] felt that she was \"underused\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2006/08/02/little_miss_sunshine_2006_review.shtml|title=BBC - Movies - review - Little Miss Sunshine|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Waxman|first=Sharon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/07/movies/07waxm.html|title=Toni Collette, Lovely When Necessary but Vulnerable Always|date=2006-05-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Released in July 2006, the film received major critical acclaim, resulting in several accolades such as four [[Academy Award]] nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], whilst Collette herself earned her second [[BAFTA]] and [[Golden Globe]] nominations for her portrayal of the family's worn-out matriarch.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |title=Awards for Toni Colette|work=[[Internet Movie Database]]|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001057/awards|accessdate=22 February 2009}}</ref> A box office success, ''Little Miss Sunshine'' went on to gross US$100.5&nbsp;million worldwide and became one of the most successful independent films of the mid-2000s.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Little Miss Sunshine'' (2006) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/LMSUN.php |work=The-Numbers.com |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ToniCollettOrangeBritishAcademyFilmAwards07.jpg|thumbnail|Collette at the Orange British Academy Film Awards in London's Royal Opera House in February 2007|left|235x235px]]\nThat same year, Collette also played supporting roles in the [[Thriller film|thriller]] films ''[[Like Minds]]'', ''[[The Night Listener (film)|The Night Listener]]'' and ''[[The Dead Girl]]''. Although the latter was released to positive reviews during its limited North American run,<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Dead Girl'' (2006)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dead_girl/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref> none of these films fared well at the box office, with [[Robin Williams]]-featuring ''The Night Listener'' emerging as the biggest-selling production with a global gross revenue of US$10.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Night Listener'' (2006)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/NTLIS.php |work=The-Numbers.com |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref> In her first television engagement in five years, the [[HBO]]-[[BBC]] joint [[miniseries]] ''[[Tsunami: The Aftermath]]'' (2006), Collette played an Australian government employee who tries to cope with the events following the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] and the resulting [[tsunami]] in Thailand. The film received mixed reviews from critics. Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' said that it was, \"inexcusably tasteless, tone deaf... and dull.\" and Brian Lowry of ''Variety'' remarked that the film, \"[grasps] for higher ground that it never reaches.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/awards/tsunami-the-aftermath-1200511645/|title=Tsunami, the Aftermath|last=Lowry|first=Brian|last2=Lowry|first2=Brian|date=2006-12-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2006-12-07-tsunami_x.htm|title=HBO's 'Tsunami' is itself a disaster, and just wrong - USATODAY.com|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> Despite this, significant praise was given to the performances of the cast.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Heffernan|first=Virginia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/08/arts/television/08tsun.html|title=Melodrama and, Oh Yes, a Tsunami|date=2006-12-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/27874/tsunami-the-aftermath/|title=Tsunami: The Aftermath|website=DVD Talk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> For her role, Collette earned her first [[Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy]] nomination and third Golden Globe nomination.<ref name=\"imdb\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/toni-collette|title=Toni Collette|work=Television Academy|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing her duties as a jury member at the [[2007 Cannes Film Festival]], she took part in two releases of 2007 - ''[[Towelhead (film)|Towelhead]]'' and ''[[Evening (film)|Evening]]''. While the former received mixed reviews the latter was almost universally panned. In a review for ''Towelhead'', Kelly Vance of ''[[East Bay Express]]'', called it \"one the most intelligent films of the year\" and praised Collette's performance. While reviewing ''Evening'', Dustin Putman called it \"flawed in more ways than one\" but lauded Collette for \"[enlivening] her scenes with pathos.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastbayexpress.com/eastbay/there-goes-the-neighborhood/Content?oid=1091720|title=There Goes the Neighborhood|last=Vance|first=Kelly|website=East Bay Express|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefilmfile.com/reviews/e/07_evening.htm|title=Dustin Putman's Review - Evening (2007) - [TheMovieBoy]|website=www.thefilmfile.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> In 2008, she played a small role in ''[[Hey, Hey, It's Esther Blueburger]]'' also serving as an [[executive producer]]. Her scenes were shot in only a week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/burger-with-the-lot/news-story/6022f9b9b91a33426510f5e729597d20|title=Burger with the lot|date=2008-01-09|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> The film received tepid reviews and failed to recoup its $6 million budget. Bernadete McNulty, writing for [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Telegraph'']], said of the film, \"Collette\u2019s presence may have got this Australian debut from writer/director Cathy Randall off the ground [but] her slight role is insufficient to make it fly the distance.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=McNulty|first=Bernadette|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/dvd-reviews/5394834/DVD-review-Hey-Hey-Its-Esther-Blueburger.html|title=DVD review: Hey Hey It's Esther Blueburger|date=2009-07-28|access-date=2020-02-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Her other film of 2008, ''[[The Black Balloon (film)|The Black Balloon]]'' was much better received. Frank Hatherley of ''[[Screen Daily]]'' praised the film and Collette's performance, writing \"Collette gives another of her warm, full-blooded portraits\" and [[Roger Ebert]] venerated her performance as being the heart of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-black-balloon-2009|title=The Black Balloon movie review (2009) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/the-black-balloon-2007/4036868.article|title=The Black Balloon (2007)|last=Hatherley2008-02-08T21:01:00+00:00|first=Frank|website=Screen|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Collette accepted the leading role in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] comedy-drama series, ''[[United States of Tara]]''. Created by [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Diablo Cody]], the show revolves around a wife and mother of two with [[dissociative identity disorder]], coping with her alternate personalities. She was given the leading role by Spielberg without having to audition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/toni-collette-5-things-you-835310/item/forces-auditions-toni-collette-835321|title=Forces Auditions - Toni Collette: 5 Things You Didn't Know About the Actress|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> For the role, Collette had to play multiple characters in the show. Collette found the role required her to prepare a bit more than she normally did. However, after she understood the characters better, she found it easier to play them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autostraddle.com/toni-collette-straddles-gender-roles-in-united-states-of-tara-the-autostraddle-interview-38058/|title=Toni Collette is Queering Gender in United States of Tara: The Autostraddle Interview|date=2010-03-22|website=Autostraddle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> The show was originally planned for a twelve-episode season, but was renewed for a second and third season after it gave the network its highest ratings since 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.multichannel.com/article/173970-Showtime_United_With_Tara_For_Second_Season.php|title=Showtime United With Tara For Second Season - 2009-02-10 21:05:39 - Multichannel News|date=2009-02-14|access-date=2020-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214045815/http://www.multichannel.com/article/173970-Showtime_United_With_Tara_For_Second_Season.php|archive-date=14 February 2009}}</ref> The series and Collette's performance received positive reviews. Tim Goodman of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' called her a \"tour de force\" and Ariana Bacle of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised Collette's \"flawless\" transition between personalities that felt so \"insanely distinct\" that they could have each been a different actor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2014/02/10/im-still-not-over-united-states-of-tara-cancellation/|title=I'm Still Not Over... 'United States of Tara' getting canceled|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/TV-review-United-States-of-Tara-3254262.php|title=TV review: 'United States of Tara'|last=Goodman|first=Tim|date=2009-01-16|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> Collette won both the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe for Best Actress in a TV Comedy]] in 2009 and was nominated for both again the following year.\n\nShe was originally set to star in ''[[Away We Go]]'' (2009) but had to drop out due to scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{Citation|title=Away We Go (2009) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1176740/trivia|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> Collette next starred as a single mother of a precocious child in ''[[Jesus Henry Christ]]'' (2011). The film received negative reviews; James Plath of ''Movie Metropolis'' called her 'terrific\" but John DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' felt that Collette was severely underutilised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moviemet.com/review/jesus-henry-christ-dvd-review|title=JESUS HENRY CHRIST - DVD review|date=2012-07-03|website=Movie Metropolis|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/jesus-henry-christ-film-review-183323|title=Jesus Henry Christ: Tribeca Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> She later had a supporting role in the horror-comedy [[Fright Night (2011 film)|''Fright Night'']] (2011). The film reunited her with filmmaker [[Craig Gillespie]] who had previously directed her in several episodes of ''United States of Tara''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2011/film/reviews/fright-night-1117945839/|title=Fright Night|last=Koehler|first=Robert|last2=Koehler|first2=Robert|date=2011-08-18|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> Debbie Lynn Elias of ''Behind The Lens'' called her \"pitchfork perfect\" while Emmet Asher-Perrin of ''[[Tor.com]]'' said that she was \"charming as always.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2011/08/23/one-of-lifes-guilty-pleasures-fright-night/|title=One of Life's Guilty Pleasures: Fright Night|last=Asher-Perrin|first=Emmet|date=2011-08-23|website=Tor.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://behindthelensonline.net/site/reviews/fright-night/|title=FRIGHT NIGHT|last=Elias|first=Debbie Lynn|website=Behind The Lens|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> ''Fright Night'' received positive reviews and was a modest commercial success grossing $41 million on a $30 million budget.\n\n===2012\u20132017: Focus on independent films and return to Broadway===\nCollette's first release of 2012 was the independent comedy-drama ''[[Mental (2012 film)|Mental]]''. She played a hitchhiker who is hired as a [[nanny]] to take care of five [[mentally ill]] sisters. Despite giving the film a negative review, Gary Goldstein of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that Collette \"rips into her woolly role as if channeling a leftover personality from her ''United States of Tara'' days\"; Luke Buckmaster of ''[[Crikey]]'' called her \"charismatic and all-inhabiting\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.crikey.com.au/cinetology/2012/10/08/mental-movie-review-crazy-good-aussie-filmmaking/|title=Mental movie review: crazy good Aussie filmmaking \u2013 Cinetology|website=blogs.crikey.com.au|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-xpm-2013-mar-28-la-et-mn-mental-capsule-review-20130329-story.html|title=Review: In a fragile 'Mental' state|date=2013-03-28|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> She received her third [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|AACTA Award for Best Actress]] nomination for her role. Later in 2012, Collette played a small supporting role in the [[Biographical film|biographical]] drama film ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]].'' [[Deborah Ross (journalist)|Deborah Ross]], writing for ''[[The Spectator]],'' gave the film an unenthusiastic review and said that the film, \"wastes many of its cast members - particularly Toni Collette.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2013/02/whats-it-all-about-3/|title=What kind of film does 'Hitchcock' think it is?|date=2013-02-09|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Collette earned critical acclaim for her work in the independent films ''[[The Way, Way Back]]'' as Pam, opposite [[Steve Carell]] and [[Sam Rockwell]], and ''[[Enough Said (film)|Enough Said]]'' as Sarah, with [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]] and [[James Gandolfini]]. For her work in ''The Way, Way Back'', Collette received several glowing reviews. Andrew O'Heir of ''[[Salon Magazine]]'' praised her \"brilliant, understated performance\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2013/07/05/pick_of_the_week_the_way_way_back_is_a_wistful_summer_escape/ |title=Pick of the week: \"The Way, Way Back\" is a wistful summer escape |first=Andrew |last=O'Hehir |date=5 July 2013 |work=[[Salon.com]] |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' dubbed her work \"stellar\";<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-way-way-back-20130708 |first=Peter |last=Travers |title=The Way Way Back |date=8 July 2013 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] described Collette as a \"chameleon\" and said that she gives a performance far and above what the role required.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reelviews.net/php_review_template.php?identifier=2639 |title=The Way Way Back |first=James |last=Berardinelli |date=16 July 2013 |work=Reelviews Movie Reviews |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> Her performance in ''Enough Said'' was also well received. Katie Smith-Wong of ''FlickFeast'' praised her for bringing humor to the film but Joseph Walsh of ''CinVue'' said that she was underused.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickfeast.co.uk/reviews/film-reviews/enoughsaid-2013-2/|title=Enough Said (2013)|date=2013-10-17|website=flickfeast|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cine-vue.com/2013/10/lff-2013-enough-said-review.html|title=LFF 2013: 'Enough Said' review|date=2013-10-20|website=CineVue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> In the fall of 2013, Collette starred in the CBS drama ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]'', which received solid reviews but weak ratings. ''[[RedEye]]'' described her performance as \"fascinating\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.redeyechicago.com/entertainment/tv/redeye-blacklist-hostages-tv-reviews-20130922,0,3522892.story |title=Monday suspense TV: 'The Blacklist' has edge over 'Hostages' |first=Curt |last=Wagner |date=22 September 2013 |work=[[RedEye]] |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> ''[[Newsday]]'' as \"superb\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/hostages-review-thrill-ride-1.6109696 |title='Hostages' review: Thrill ride |first=Verne |last=Gay |date=20 September 2013 |work=Newsday |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> and ''[[USA Today]]'' as \"nuanced\" and \"grounded.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/09/22/bianco-blacklist-hostages-combo-review-sept-23/2831619/ | work=USA Today | first1=Robert | last1=Bianco | title='Blacklist,' 'Hostages' each have suspenseful charms | date=22 September 2013}}</ref> The series aired for fifteen episodes and, due to a combination of low ratings and a closed narrative, did not return for a second season.\n\n[[File:Toni Collette (8968233309).jpg|alt=|thumb|275x275px|Collette at ''[[The Way Way Back]]'' premiere at the State Theatre, Sydney in 2013]]\nIn the comedy-drama ''[[Lucky Them]]'' (also 2013), which debuted at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], Collette played a music critic who is assigned to write a piece on a disappeared musician and childhood sweetheart, subsequently tasking herself to track him down. The film earned mostly positive reviews, with Collette receiving the bulk of the praise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2014-05-28/film/lucky-them-movie/ |title=The Nimble Lucky Them Seeks Out a Grunge Legend |first=Chris |last=Packham |date=28 May 2014 |work=Village Voice |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://nypost.com/2014/05/28/indie-charmer-lucky-them-boasts-a-rock-solid-cast/ | work=New York Post | first=Lou | last=Lumenick | title=Indie charmer 'Lucky Them' boasts a rock solid cast | date=28 May 2014}}</ref> David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that the movie was \"centered by smart, soulful work by the wonderful Toni Collette\" and that she played her character \"with warmth, realness and emotional transparency that make you stay with her even when she's pushing people away\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lucky-toronto-review-625953 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=David | last=Rooney | title=Lucky Them: Toronto Review | date=11 September 2013}}</ref> The film also screened at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], where Joe Bendel of ''[[Libertas Film Magazine]]'' ranked her performance as the fourth-best of the festival, and upon release, [[Mike D'Angelo]] of ''[[The Dissolve]]'' wrote that Collette \"is capable of anything.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/results-of-the-2014-tribeca-critics-poll |title=Critics Pick the Best Movies at the Tribeca Film Festival |first=Steve |last=Greene |date=29 April 2014 |work=Indiewire |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thedissolve.com/reviews/832-lucky-them/|accessdate=8 July 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324181848/https://thedissolve.com/reviews/832-lucky-them/|archivedate=24 March 2015 |title=Lucky Them|last=Klimek|first=Chris|date=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 14-year absence, Collette returned to Broadway in 2014, starring in [[Will Eno]]'s play ''[[The Realistic Joneses]]'', in which she co-starred alongside [[Michael C. Hall]], [[Tracy Letts]] and [[Marisa Tomei]]. The play examines a couple who project its insecurities and fears onto their next-door neighbors with the same last name. The play opened to positive reviews, with Collette and the entire cast earning high praise.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Review-Roundup-THE-REALISTIC-JONESES-Opens-on-Broadway-Updating-Live-20140406# |title=Review Roundup: \"The Realistic Joneses\" Opens on Broadway |work=Broadway World |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> A rave review from ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that \"Ms. Collette exudes a touching, exasperated dignity as Jennifer.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/07/theater/realistic-joneses-stars-toni-collette-and-michael-c-hall.html |title=Realistic Joneses Stars Toni Collette And Michael C. Hall |newspaper=The New York Times |date=7 April 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called her work \"terribly funny,\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-the-realistic-joneses-1201153252/ |title=Broadway Review: 'The Realistic Joneses' |first=Marilyn |last=Stasio |work=Variety |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> while ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' claimed that \"Collette, whose naturalness can cut through even the very deliberate theatrical artifice of Eno's dialogue and scene construction, anchors the play with her somber restraint and deadpan delivery.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/theater-review-realistic-joneses-693966 |title=Theater Review: The Realistic Joneses |first=David |last=Rooney |work=Hollywood Reporter |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> The ''[[New York Post]]'', which was more critical of the play, highlighted Collette's performance: \"Collette does some heavy lifting to fill in Eno's blanks. You can read deep sadness in the wide planes of her expressive face, in her lost, unfocused eyes.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2014/04/06/eno-packs-powerhouse-quartet-in-the-realistic-joneses/ |title=Eno packs powerhouse quartet in 'The Realistic Joneses' |first=Elisabeth |last=Vincentelli |newspaper=New York Post |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> Collette and her co-stars won a [[Drama Desk Special Award]] for Best Ensemble Performance.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2014/legit/news/gentlemans-guide-racks-up-a-dozen-nominations-for-the-2014-drama-desk-awards-1201163848/ | work=Variety | first=Gordon | last=Cox | title='Gentleman's Guide' Racks Up 12 Nominations for Drama Desk Awards | date=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Collette appeared in the black comedy ''[[A Long Way Down (film)|A Long Way Down]]'', the comedies ''[[Tammy (film)|Tammy]]'' and ''[[Hector and the Search for Happiness (film)|Hector and the Search for Happiness]]'', the drama ''[[Glassland]]'', and lent her voice to the animated film ''[[The Boxtrolls]]''. Except for the lattermost, none of these films were significantly successful, either critically or commercially, and her presence in each were considered to be wasted. She starred opposite [[Drew Barrymore]] in the comedy-drama ''[[Miss You Already]]'' (2015), about two women whose friendship is tested when one of them starts a family while the other falls ill. The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] to generally positive reviews, with Billy Goodykoontz of the ''Arizona Republic'' asserting that \"Collette's work is so compulsively watchable that ''Miss You Already'' is worth a watch for that reason alone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/movies/billgoodykoontz/2015/11/05/miss-you-already-old-fashioned-weepie-movie-review/75134050/|title=Review: 'Miss You Already' an old-fashioned weepie|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Collette then played the matriarch of a dysfunctional family in the horror film ''[[Krampus (film)|Krampus]]'' (also 2015), which was a moderate commercial success, grossing $61.5 million against a budget of $15 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=krampus.htm|title=Krampus (2015)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> Collette's sole release of 2016 was the crime thriller ''[[Imperium]]'' opposite [[Daniel Radcliffe]] as an FBI analyst targeting a white supremacist group. Despite its limited release, the film garnered positive reviews, with Gary Goldstein of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' calling it \"impressively dimensional...tense, gripping and disturbing,\" and found Collette to be \"excellent\" in her role as Radcliffe's character's supervisor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-imperium-review-20160816-snap-story.html |title= Daniel Radcliffe goes undercover with white supremacists in crime thriller 'Imperium' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Collette starred in a myriad of films, all to varying degrees of success. The action film, ''[[XXX: Return of Xander Cage]]'', starring [[Vin Diesel]], was a commercial success, grossing $346.1 million<ref name=\"BOM2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=xxx3.htm|title=xXx: The Return of Xander Cage (2017)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 22, 2017}}</ref> and earned mixed reviews, though Mick LaSalle of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' praised Collette for \"embrac[ing] the cold-blooded extremes of her role\" as a CIA operative.<ref>https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/XXX-Return-of-Xander-Cage-OK-if-10869299.php</ref> Her next two films\u2014the war drama ''[[The Yellow Birds (film)|The Yellow Birds]]'' and the comedy ''[[Fun Mom Dinner]]''\u2014premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundance.org/pdf/film-guide/SFF17_FilmGuide_Web_Dec12.pdf|title=2017 Sundance Film Festival: Printable Film Guide|website=[[Sundance Film Festival]]|publisher=[[The Sundance Institute]]|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref> Both films garnered mixed reviews, though Collette's work was appreciated, particularly in the former, with Michael Rechtshaffen of the ''Los Angeles Times'' taking note of how she and co-star [[Jennifer Aniston]] \"deliver uniformly naturalistic performances.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-yellow-birds-review-20180614-story.html|title=Though well-acted, 'The Yellow Birds' relies too heavily on previous war dramas|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=14 June 2018|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref> Also in 2017 she starred in the action-thriller ''[[Unlocked (2017 film)|Unlocked]]'', and the comedies ''[[Madame (2017 film)|Madame]]'' and ''[[Please Stand By]]'', all of which were lambasted by critics. The mystery drama ''[[Jasper Jones (film)|Jasper Jones]]'' (2017) was much better received. Sandra Hall of ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' praised Collette's emotional range and James Douglas, writing for ''The Guardian'', said that she was \"impossibly vivacious as always\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Douglas|first=James Robert|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/aug/25/jasper-jones-first-look-review-spielberg-meets-stranger-things-in-australian-coming-of-age-tale|title=Jasper Jones first look review \u2013 Spielberg meets Stranger Things in Australian coming-of-age tale|date=2016-08-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/jasper-jones-review-a-classic-tale-well-told-20170227-gum3uf.html|title=Jasper Jones review: A classic tale well told|last=Hall|first=Sandra|date=2017-02-28|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref> Richard Kuipers of ''Variety'' eulogized Collette's climactic monologue in which her character laments her discontent, calling Collette \"positively electrifying\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/jasper-jones-film-review-1201999791/|title=Film Review: 'Jasper Jones'|last=Kuipers|first=Richard|last2=Kuipers|first2=Richard|date=2017-03-02|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Mainstream films and Netflix===\nIn 2018, Collette gave what many critics considered to be the best performance of her career in the horror film ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]'', in which she played the matriarch of a family haunted by the supernatural following the death of her mother.<ref name=rolling>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/hereditary-inside-the-making-of-a-modern-horror-classic-629141/|title=Hereditary': Inside the Making of a Modern Horror Classic|author=Fear, David|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=December 23, 2018}}</ref> Collette was initially reluctant to take on the role, but was ultimately convinced by the script's grounded approach and its exploration of grief and loss.<ref name=\":2\" /> She considered the role to have been the most difficult of her career. In an interview with ''Vulture,'' she reflected, \"There was no easy moment in this movie... I was shooting 14-take scenes, talking about great loss and difficulty in relating to my family\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/toni-collette-on-hereditary-the-wildest-movie-of-her-career.html|title=Toni Collette on Hereditary, the Wildest Movie of Her Career|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=2018-06-08|website=Vulture|language=en-us|accessdate=2020-02-15}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] to critical acclaim, and it became [[A24 (company)|A24]]'s highest-grossing film, earning $80.2 million<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sundance.org/projects/hereditary |title=Hereditary |work=[[Sundance Film Festival]] |publisher=[[The Sundance Institute]] |accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> Chris Nashawaty of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised Collette for her \"real dramatic power and force,\" while Michael Phillips of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' complimented her \"fierce performance with a human pulse\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-hereditary-rev-0604-story.html|title='Hereditary' review: Toni Collette reveals a sixth sense for icy terror|last=Phillips|first=Michael|work=chicagotribune.com|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/06/08/hereditary-movie-review-toni-collette/|title=Toni Collette is scary good in the terrifying 'Hereditary': EW review|work=EW.com|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=en}}</ref> She won the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actress]] and was nominated for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]] for her performance.\n\n[[File:Toni Collette (48707296653) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Collette at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] premiere of ''[[Knives Out]]'' (2019)]]\n''[[Wanderlust (British TV series)|Wanderlust]]'' (2018), a [[BBC One]] drama series about the troubled relationship between a therapist and her husband marked Collette's first lead role in television since ''Hostages''. Collette served as an associate producer on the series.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/10/wanderlust-netflix-review-toni-collette-bbc-1202013432/|title='Wanderlust' Review: Toni Collette's Dominance of 2018 Continues in a Smart Netflix Series That's Honest About Sex|last=Travers|first=Ben|last2=Travers|first2=Ben|date=2018-10-19|website=IndieWire|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref> Ben Travers of ''[[IndieWire]]'' wrote that Collette \"[guides] the [series] through turbulent emotional seas with assurance\" and Jen Chaney of ''Vulture'' remarked that the show was worth watching solely for Collette's performance.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/wanderlust-netflix-review.html|title=In Wanderlust, Toni Collette Gets Serious About Sex|last=Chaney|first=Jen|date=2018-10-18|website=Vulture|language=en-us|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref> Also that same year, she appeared in the critically acclaimed comedy ''[[Hearts Beat Loud]]'', which also premiered at Sundance. [[Peter Bradshaw]] called the film \"a likable heartwarmer\" and praised Collette for \"[giving the] film some sinew in her supporting role\".\n\nIn 2019, Collette again ventured into the horror genre in [[Dan Gilroy]]'s ''[[Velvet Buzzsaw]]'', starring [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] and [[Rene Russo]]. A satire about the art world, the film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] to polarizing reactions. [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film a positive review and wrote, \"Collette [is] as good as we\u2019d expect [her] to be\". She then played a supporting role in [[Rian Johnson]]'s critically acclaimed mystery thriller ''[[Knives Out]]'', alongside an ensemble cast including [[Daniel Craig]], [[Ana de Armas]], [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], and [[Christopher Plummer]], among others. The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] and was a commercial success, grossing $300.1 million. Critics especially highlighted the performances of the film's cast: David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' considered Collette to be \"divine as a deeply sincere phony.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/knives-out-tiff-2019-1237825 |title='Knives Out': Film Review {{!}} TIFF 2019|last=Rooney|first=David|date=September 7, 2019|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909090941/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/knives-out-tiff-2019-1237825|archive-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCollette then took on the role of a detective investigating a troubling rape case alongside [[Merritt Wever]] and [[Kaitlyn Dever]] in the [[Netflix]] miniseries ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]'' (2019). She had accepted the role prior to having read the script, finding it \"important and so meaningful\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/toni-collette-interview-unbelievable/#nightmare-alley-knives-out|title=Toni Collette on Unbelievable, Knives Out and Nightmare Alley|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> She prepared for the role by having a female cop on set who helped her with such particulars as where to place badges and guns and how to stage a medical examination with a rape victim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/09/10/script-for-unbelievable-made-toni-collettes-blood-boil/|title=Script for \u2018Unbelievable\u2019 made Toni Collette\u2019s blood boil|last=Rorke|first=Robert|date=2019-09-10|website=New York Post|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref> The series had been viewed by over 32 million viewers making it one of Netflix's highest viewed television series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/netflix-has-revealed-its-most-watched-content-you-might-be-surprised-1.4060255|title=Netflix has revealed its most-watched content. You might be surprised|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Collette received acclaim for her performance and several critics praised her chemistry with Wever.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/reviews/unbelievable-netflix-review-toni-collette-merritt-wever-1203304722/|title=TV Review: 'Unbelievable'|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|last2=D'Addario|first2=Daniel|date=2019-09-03|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.ie/tv/on-demand/review-unbelievable-netflix-disturbing-gripping-419080/|title=Review: 'Unbelievable' may be one of Netflix's most disturbing shows but it's utterly gripping|last=Flynn|first=Fiona|website=Entertainment.ie|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref> She received her sixth [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] nomination and won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Movie/Miniseries]].\n\nIn 2020, she took on a leading role in [[Dream Horse (film)|''Dream Horse'']] playing a middle-aged [[South Wales]] native who decides to train a racehorse. Dennis Harvey of ''Variety'' praised Collette for \"easily [carrying] the film\u2019s emotional weight.\" She will next star in two Netflix projects; the thriller series, ''[[Pieces of Her (TV series)|Pieces of Her]]'' and [[Charlie Kaufman]]'s ''[[I'm Thinking of Ending Things (film)|I'm Thinking of Ending Things]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/pieces-of-her-toni-collette-star-netflix-thriller-series-minkie-spiro-direct-1202848386/|title=Toni Collette To Star In 'Pieces Of Her' Netflix Drama Series|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=February 3, 2020|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toni-collette-jessie-buckley-and-david-thewlis-join-charlie-kaufmans-netflix-movie-exclusive-1203172412/|title=Toni Collette, Jessie Buckley and David Thewlis Join Charlie Kaufman's Netflix Movie (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-03-26|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref> She has also committed to star in the science fiction thriller ''[[Stowaway (upcoming film)|Stowaway]]'' and [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s ''[[Nightmare Alley (upcoming film)|Nightmare Alley]]'' (all 2020)''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toni-collette-anna-kendrick-stowaway-1203107585/|title=Toni Collette Joins Anna Kendrick in Sci-Fi Thriller 'Stowaway' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|date=2019-01-15|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n[[File:Miss You Already 05 (20764762454) (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|240x240px|Collette at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] premiere of ''[[Miss You Already]]'' (2015)]]\nDespite cherishing music and singing at a young age, Collette had stopped singing in the mid 1990s as she felt uncomfortable doing so, remarking \"[Singing] comes from a very personal place. It's your voice... and it's only in the last couple of years I felt comfortable in myself singing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tonicollette.org/videos/videos/the-wild-party-rehearsals-2000/|title=Toni Collette Video Archives \u00bb The Wild Party \u2013 Rehearsals|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> In 1996, she sang three covers for the soundtrack of the film ''Cosi''. She sang \"[[Don't Dream It's Over]]\" by [[Crowded House]], \"[[Stand by Me (Ben E. King song)|Stand By Me]]\" by [[Ben E. King]] and \"[[Throw Your Arms Around Me]]\" by [[Hunters & Collectors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringostrack.com:443/en/movie/cosi/81853|title=Cosi (1996) Soundtrack|website=RingosTrack|language=en |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> In 2000, she recorded nine songs for the cast album ''The Wild Party'' for the eponymous Broadway musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Wild-Party-Various-artists/dp/B000V889OK |title=The Wild Party |website=www.amazon.com|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> Elyse Sommer of ''CurtainUp,'' in a review of the musical, wrote that Collette was a \"topnotch singer\" and particularly praised her rendition of the song \"People Like Us\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curtainup.com/wildparty2.html|title=The Wild Party, a CurtainUp review|website=www.curtainup.com|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> For the soundtrack of ''Connie and Carla'', Collette recorded renditions of several famous songs including \"[[I'm Gonna Wash That Man Right Outa My Hair]]\", \"[[Maybe This Time (song)|Maybe This Time]]\" and \"[[Cabaret (Cabaret song)|Cabaret]]\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Connie and Carla (2004) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0345074/soundtrack|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> David Haviland of ''Eye For Film'' praised the renditions, writing, \"The musical numbers are a [[Camp (style)|camp]] triumph.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/connie-and-carla-do-la-film-review-by-david-haviland|title=Connie And Carla Do LA (2004) Movie Review from Eye for Film|website=www.eyeforfilm.co.uk|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> She sang the track \"Sunday Morning\" for the album ''[[Summertown (album)|Summertown]]'' by [[Deborah Conway]] and Willy Zygier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Deborah-Conway-Willy-Zygier-Summertown/release/1987120|title=Deborah Conway & Willy Zygier - Summertown|website=Discogs|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> She has also performed songs for the soundtracks of many other films including ''About a Boy,  A Long Way Down, Miss You Already'' and ''Hearts Beat Loud''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001057/|title=Toni Collette {{!}} Refer to Soundtrack|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nCollette has been writing songs since she was in her early teens.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|last=Dubecki|first=Larissa|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/music/tonis-hidden-talent/2006/11/01/1162339920182.html?page=fullpage|title=Toni's hidden talent|date=3 November 2006|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref> In 2006, she along with her husband Dave Galafassi, [[Amanda Brown (musician)|Amanda Brown]], [[Glenn Richards]], [[David Lane (musician)|David Lane]] and Pete Farley formed the band [[Toni Collette & the Finish]], with Collette serving as the lead singer. In October 2006, the band produced their debut album, ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'', released on Hoola Hoop Records.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Toni-Collette-The-Finish-Beautiful-Awkward-Pictures/release/4776219|title=Toni Collette & The Finish - Beautiful Awkward Pictures|website=Discogs|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> Using her personal life as an inspiration, Collette wrote all the eleven tracks by herself.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tonicollette.org/articles/200611thesydneymorningherald/|title=The Little Drummer Girl|last=|first=|date=|website=m.webwombat.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> The [[pop rock]]<ref name=\":9\" /> album was recorded in two weeks.<ref name=\":8\" /> Eclectic of ''[[Sputnikmusic]]'' gave the album a positive review and wrote, \"Collette\u2019s subdued vocals aren\u2019t perfect, but they\u2019re close enough to love all the same\". He did, however, rebuke the lyrics of some tracks remarking that they had \"some stunningly bad lines\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/41593/Toni-Collette-and-The-Finish-Beautiful-Awkward-Pictures/|title=Toni Collette and The Finish - Beautiful Awkward Pictures (album review ) {{!}} Sputnikmusic|website=www.sputnikmusic.com|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> Collette appeared on the Australian television show ''Cool Aid'' and performed the song \"Look Up\" from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/toni-collette/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Toni Collette|last=Hanson-Firestone|first=Dana|date=2019-10-17|website=TVOvermind|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> In July 2007, Toni Collette & the Finish headlined at the Sydney show of [[Live Earth]], singing a cover of [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]]'s \"[[Children of the Revolution (song)|Children of the Revolution]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sams|first=Christine|title=Sydney's giant, jolly green gig|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/music/sydneys-giant-jolly-green-gig/2007/07/07/1183351525552.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 July 2007}}</ref> In 2012, she expressed her desire to make another album, but said that she found it difficult to find enough time to commit to the project.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/interview-toni-collette/|title=Interview: Toni Collette on Hitchcock, The Sixth Sense, and More|last=Osenlund|first=R. Kurt|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Humanitarian work==\n[[File:Toni Collette (6902409149) (cropped).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|240x240px|Collette at the 2012 [[Tropfest]] in Sydney]]\nCollette supports various charities including [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Border]], [[Amnesty International]] and [[Feeding America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/celebrity/toni-collette|title=Toni Collette: Charity Work & Causes|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> She has expressed her support for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] and, in 2005, wrote a letter to then [[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian Prime Minister]] [[John Howard]], asking him to ban the practice of [[mulesing]] and the live export of sheep.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/toni-not-sheepish-20050701-ge0fzc.html|title=Toni not sheepish|date=2005-07-01|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In 2009, Collette auctioned off several T-shirts of her own design to raise money for various charities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/2677-celebrities-do-whatever-it-takes-for-charity|title=Celebrities Do Whatever It Takes For Charity|date=2009-06-15|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Collette along with [[Drew Barrymore]] and [[Catherine Hardwicke]] took part in an event for a breast cancer charity. She wore [[Breast cancer awareness|pink ribbons]] to support [[Breast Cancer Awareness Month]] to the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbookmag.com/beauty-fashion/blogs/trends/toni-collette-shaved-head|title=Toni Collette Has a Bold New Look|last=Friedman|first=Megan|date=2014-10-10|website=Redbook|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She has taken part in an event to raise money for \"OzHarvest\", an organisation which collects excess food from some of Australia's restaurants and redistributes it to the homeless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/toni-collette-helps-aussie-food-charity/news-story/feb277c255798bca3ee0c186576b603e|title=Collette helps Aussie food charity|date=2009-10-19|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She sold some of her personal items for an auction to raise money for the charity \"Cure Our Kids\" which is dedicated to raising money for the [[oncology]] unit at [[The Children\u2019s Hospital at Westmead]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/1469-lleyton-hewitt-launches-charity-auction|title=Lleyton Hewitt Launches Charity Auction|date=2008-10-28|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, she was part of the host committee to hold the third annual Go Go Gala which will benefit the [[GO Campaign]] which seeks to help orphans and vulnerable children throughout the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/5375-ewan-mcgregor-to-host-celebrity-charity-go-go-gala|title=Ewan McGregor To Host Celebrity Charity Go Go Gala|date=2010-11-17|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She took part in the promotion of the documentary ''[[The Lazarus Effect (2010 film)|The Lazarus Effect]]'' (2010), being featured in a small clip which sought to raise awareness of the positive impact of free [[antiretroviral drug]] therapy for those living with [[HIV]] in [[Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/4323-bono-leads-celebrity-psa-for-red-charity|title=Bono Leads Celebrity PSA For (RED) Charity|date=2010-05-02|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In 2012, Collette has contributed an exclusive blog on the fight against hunger and a call to action for [[Giving Tuesday]] and the holiday season to the [[Huffington post|Huffington Post]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/9347-stars-support-giving-tuesday|title=Stars Support Giving Tuesday|date=2012-11-27|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she was appointed as a global ambassador for [[Concern Worldwide]]. She made her first field visit with Concern to [[Haiti]] where she met families who, together with Concern, are working to break the cycle of extreme poverty. She had previously raised money for Concern\u2019s global campaign to fight hunger and malnutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.concernusa.org/story/toni-collette-is-concerns-new-global-ambassador/|title=Toni Collette is Concern\u2019s new global ambassador|website=Concern Worldwide|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> She has taken part in multiple [[Public service announcement|Public Service Announcements]] by Concern requesting the viewers to donate to Concern's various campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/49709122|title=Toni Collette and Concern Worldwide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/52887032|title=Toni Collette presents the perfect gift|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2017, she attended the 25th Annual [[Elton John AIDS Foundation Academy Award Party]] which seeks to raise money to support innovative HIV prevention, education programs and direct care and support services to people living with HIV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/16377-25th-annual-elton-john-aids-foundation-academy-awards-viewing-party-raises-record-breaking-7-million|title=25th Annual Elton John AIDS Foundation Academy Awards Viewing Party Raises Record-Breaking $7 Million|date=2017-02-28|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She has expressed her support for the [[Me Too movement]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[Sharon Waxman]] of ''The New York Times'' noted that Collette often embraces characters who are pathetic, insecure or otherwise unattractive.<ref name=\":6\" /> However, Collette has said that she detests playing such characters remarking, \" If I keep perpetuating that image of myself \u2014 that of a downtrodden person \u2014 that's the only roles I'll get. And I'm getting tired of playing those roles.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> Despite achieving stardom early in her career with the top-grossing ''The Sixth Sense'', Colette has rarely acted in commerce-driven pictures. She often prefers working in [[independent film]] over [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbusters]] as she feels the latter tend to prioritize box-office success over telling a story.<ref name=\":7\" /> Several journalists have noted Collette's gravitation towards playing dissatisfied and slightly neurotic mothers. When asked about being [[Typecasting|typecast]] in such roles, Collette replied, \"All people are different. All women are different. A lot of women haven\u2019t had children but it doesn\u2019t change the fact that they\u2019re individuals and have some kind of individuality and spark about them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wise|first=Damon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/16/toni-collette-every-scene-was-like-being-punched-glassland|title=Toni Collette: 'Every scene was like being punched'|date=2015-04-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>{{Quote box\n| quote = \"I try to put myself in the position of the character and feel things as holistically as I can. It\u2019s an exhausting way to do it. I\u2019m not [going to] recommend it to anybody, but that\u2019s the only way I know how to do it.\"\n| source = {{snd}} Collette on her acting style<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/toni-collette-on-hereditary-the-wildest-movie-of-her-career.html|title=Toni Collette on Hereditary, the Wildest Movie of Her Career|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=2018-06-08|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width = 20%\n| bgcolor = #E0E6F8\n}}Collette has listed [[Geoffrey Rush]] as one of her influences.<ref name=\":3\" /> She has said that she does not find it difficult to detach herself from her roles, but reflected that after doing several heavy thematic films she, \"[started] to find things were accumulating. I had to figure out a way to kind of shake it off. So I am figuring that out.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/toni-collette-hereditary-interview/|title=Toni Collette Tells Us The Scariest Thing About 'Hereditary' [Interview]|date=2018-06-08|website=/Film|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> When asked how she decides to play her characters, Collette replied, \"When I look at a character, I never look at the size of the role. I always look at the whole person, no matter how much they're featured in the movie\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/q-and-a-toni-collette/|title=Q&A: Toni Collette Actor, Hostages and Enough Said|last=|first=|date=23 September 2013|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She has stated that she dislikes working with [[dialect coach]]es, in order to prepare for an accent, as they make her feel self-conscious.<ref>{{Citation|title=Art of Film: Accents, Dialects and Acting with Saoirse Ronan & Toni Collette|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3QFFnFtQufM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> Although she has gained weight to play characters in previous films, Collette dislikes doing so, and after filming ''In Her Shoes'', said that she would never put on weight for a film ever again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/toni-collette-worth-the-weight-326193.html|title=Toni Collette: Worth the weight|date=2005-11-11|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> [[Brie Larson]], who starred with Collette in ''United States of Tara'', has cited her as an inspiration and praised her for being able to \"disappear\" into her roles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cBTvu66vc7g|title=THR Roundtable {{!}} Play the video at 7:58 for the quote|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Greg Kinnear]], her co-star in ''Dinner with Friends'' and ''Little Miss Sunshine,'' called her \"gifted\" and commended her for being able to communicate without dialogue.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nRilla Kingston in an analysis of Collette's acting style, compared her to character actress [[Thelma Ritter]] who was also widely critically acclaimed for her supporting roles and repeatedly typecast as the female comic second. Kingston took note of Collette's use of physicality to convey her characters' emotions as in ''Emma'' and ''United States of Tara''. She remarked that Collette's acting method references the components of [[Stanislavski's system|Stanislavski\u2019s System of Acting]]. In studying Collette's typecasting as mothers, Kingston wrote, \"[Collette] selectively chooses roles of women and mothers which she can portray in ways that are multidimensional and different from another.\" She also wrote that Collette makes conscious efforts to break from the typecasting, with leading roles in films like ''Miss You Already'' and ''Lucky Them''. At the end of her analysis, Kingston concluded, \"Collette truly is a chameleon in both the versatility of her acting style and in the kind of roles she is willing to approach with a physicality-based method.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcgillchannelundergraduatereview.com/2018/04/toni-collette-character-as-craft/|title=Toni Collette: Character as Craft \u2013 The Channel|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Toni Collette by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|236x236px|Collette at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic Con]] promoting [[Krampus (film)|''Krampus'']] (2015)|alt=]]\nIn 1998, she stayed in a flat in [[Brixton]] for a few months before leaving after she saw a man \"getting his head bashed in with a pole 30 metres away\".<ref name=\":11\" /> She briefly lived in [[Sydney]] in the 2000s before she moved to [[Los Angeles]], where she currently resides with her family.<ref name=\":11\" /> However, she has said that she and her husband plan to return to Sydney some day.<ref name=\":11\" /> Collette had dated ''Velvet Goldmine'' co-star [[Jonathan Rhys Meyers|Jonathan Rhys-Meyers]] for a year before ending their relationship. She later described the relationship as \"hedonistic, drunken and probably dangerous.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> When asked about her faith, she remarked, \"We're all spiritual... I'm not [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] but I am drawn to it because it seems the most beneficial of organised religions, and the most compassionate. It's an ongoing journey\". She met musician Dave Galafassi at the CD launch for his then band [[Gelbison]].<ref name=\":10\" /> Collette married Galafassi in a traditional Buddhist ceremony on 11 January 2003.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benns|first=Matthew|last2=Sams|first2=Christine|title=Toni's wedding|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/01/12/1041990146127.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=12 January 2003}}</ref> The couple have a daughter, Sage Florence, born on 9 January 2008,<ref>{{cite news|last=Tan|first=Michelle|title=Toni Collette Has a Girl|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20170375,00.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=10 January 2008}}</ref> and a son, Arlo Robert, born on 22 April 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chi|first=Paul|last2=Jordan|first2=Julie|title=Toni Collette Is a Mom \u2013 Again!|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20484453,00.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=People|date=25 April 2011}}</ref> She has said that she is an avid camper and she enjoys meditating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indexmagazine.com/interviews/toni_collette.shtml|title=Toni Collette with Ariana Speyer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.indexmagazine.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Years\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Spotswood (film)|Spotswood]]''\n| 1992\n| Wendy Robinson\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''This Marching Girl Thing''\n| 1994\n| Cindy\n| Short film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Muriel's Wedding]]''\n| 1994\n| Muriel Heslop\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Thief and the Cobbler]]''\n| 1995\n| Princess Yum Yum's Nanny Witch\n| Voice (Miramax version)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Clockers (film)|Clockers]]''\n| 1995\n| Virginia Martin\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Cos\u00ec (film)|Cos\u00ec]]''\n| 1996\n| Julie\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Pallbearer]]''\n| 1996\n| Cynthia\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]''\n| 1996\n| Harriet Smith\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Lilian's Story]]''\n| 1996\n| Young Lilian Singer\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Clockwatchers]]''\n| 1997\n| Iris Chapman\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The James Gang''\n| 1997\n| Julia Armstrong\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Diana & Me]]''\n| 1997\n| Diana Spencer\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Boys (1998 film)|The Boys]]''\n| 1998\n| Michelle\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Velvet Goldmine]]''\n| 1998\n| Mandy Slade\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[8\u00bd Women]]''\n| 1999\n| Griselda/Sister Concordia\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Sixth Sense]]''\n| 1999\n| Lynn Sear\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Shaft (2000 film)|Shaft]]''\n| 2000\n| Diane Palmieri\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hotel Splendide (2000 film)|Hotel Splendide]]''\n| 2000\n| Kath\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Magic Pudding (film)|The Magic Pudding]]''\n| 2000\n| Meg Bluegum\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Changing Lanes]]''\n| 2002\n| Michelle\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[About a Boy (film)|About a Boy]]''\n| 2002\n| Fiona Brewer\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Dirty Deeds (2002 film)|Dirty Deeds]]''\n| 2002\n| Sharon\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Hours (film)|The Hours]]''\n| 2002\n| Kitty\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Japanese Story]]''\n| 2003\n| Sandy Edwards\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Last Shot]]''\n| 2004\n| Emily French\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Connie and Carla]]''\n| 2004\n| Carla\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[In Her Shoes (film)|In Her Shoes]]''\n| 2005\n| Rose Feller\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]''\n| 2006\n| Sheryl Hoover\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Night Listener (film)|The Night Listener]]''\n| 2006\n| Donna D. Logand\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Like Minds]]''\n| 2006\n| Sally Rowe\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Dead Girl]]''\n| 2006\n| Arden\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Evening (film)|Evening]]''\n| 2007\n| Nina Mars\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Towelhead (film)|Towelhead]]''\n| 2007\n| Melina Hines\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Black Balloon (film)|The Black Balloon]]''\n| 2008\n| Maggie Mollison\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hey, Hey, It's Esther Blueburger]]''\n| 2008\n| Mary\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mary and Max]]''\n| 2009\n| Mary Daisy Dinkle\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Jesus Henry Christ]]''\n| 2011\n| Patricia Herman\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fright Night (2011 film)|Fright Night]]''\n| 2011\n| Jane Brewster\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Foster (film)|Foster]]''\n| 2011\n| Zooey\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]]''\n| 2012\n| [[Peggy Robertson]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mental (2012 film)|Mental]]''\n| 2012\n| Sharon \"Shaz\" Thornbender\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Way, Way Back]]''\n| 2013\n| Pam\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Enough Said]]''\n| 2013\n| Sarah\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[Lucky Them]]''\n| 2013\n| Ellie Klug\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[A Long Way Down (film)|A Long Way Down]]''\n| 2014\n| Maureen Thompson\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |  ''[[Tammy (film)|Tammy]]''\n| 2014\n| Missi Jenkins\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hector and the Search for Happiness (film)|Hector and the Search for Happiness]]''\n| 2014\n| Agnes\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Boxtrolls]]''\n| 2014\n| Lady Portley Rind\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Glassland]]''\n| 2014\n| Jean\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Blinky Bill the Movie]]''\n| 2015\n| Beryl and Cheryl\n| Voice\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Miss You Already]]''\n| 2015\n| Milly\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Krampus (film)|Krampus]]''\n| 2015\n| Sarah Engel\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Imperium (2016 film)|Imperium]]''\n| 2016\n| Angela Zamparo\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Jasper Jones (film)|Jasper Jones]]''\n| 2017\n| Ruth Bucktin\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[XXX: Return of Xander Cage]]''\n| 2017\n| Jane Marke\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Yellow Birds (film)|The Yellow Birds]]''\n| 2017\n| Amy Bartle\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Fun Mom Dinner]]''\n| 2017\n| Kate\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Unlocked (2017 film)|Unlocked]]''\n| 2017\n| Emily Knowles\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Madame (2017 film)|Madame]]''\n| 2017\n| Anne Fredericks\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Please Stand By]]''\n| 2017\n| Scottie\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]''\n| 2018\n| Annie Graham\n| Also executive producer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Hearts Beat Loud]]''\n| 2018\n| Leslie\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Birthmarked (film)|Birthmarked]]''\n| 2018\n| Catherine\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Velvet Buzzsaw]]''\n| 2019\n| Gretchen\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Knives Out]]''\n| 2019\n| Joni Thrombey\n| \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[Dream Horse (film)|Dream Horse]]''\n| 2020\n| Jan Vokes\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Stowaway (upcoming film)|Stowaway]]''\n| 2020\n| \n| Post-production\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[I'm Thinking of Ending Things (film)|I'm Thinking of Ending Things]]''\n| TBA\n|\n| Post-production\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Nightmare Alley (upcoming film)|Nightmare Alley]]''\n| TBA\n| Zeena Krumbein\n| Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Years\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[A Country Practice]]''\n| 1990\n| Tracy\n| Episode: \"The Sting: Part 1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Dinner with Friends]]''\n| 2001\n| Beth\n| Television movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Tsunami: The Aftermath]]''\n| 2006\n| Kathy Graham\n| Television movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[United States of Tara]]''\n| 200