{"title_page": "Johann Gottfried Schicht", "text_new": "{{About|the German composer and conductor|the German-Czech entrepreneur|Johann Schicht}}\n{{more references|date=February 2010}}\n[[File:Johann Gottfried Schicht.jpg|250px|thumb|Johann Gottfried Schicht]]\n'''Johann Gottfried Schicht''' (29 September 1753 &ndash; 16 February 1823) was a [[Germany|German]] [[composer]] and [[Conducting|conductor]].\n\nSchicht was born in [[Bogatynia|Reichenau]], in the [[Electorate of Saxony]]. He trained as a lawyer, studying from 1776 at Leipzig. He was the conductor of the [[Leipzig Gewandhaus Orchestra]] from 1785 to 1810, when he was succeeded by [[Johann Philipp Christian Schulz]]. Schicht continued to work in Leipzig, serving as [[Thomaskantor]], director of the [[Thomanerchor]] with responsibility for music in the city's churches. He was in post from 1810 until 1823, when he died, aged 69, in Leipzig.\n\n<!-- Schicht wirkte als [[Akkompagnist]] und [[Violinist]] an den von [[Johann Adam Hiller]] veranstalteten Konzerten (''Gro\u00dfes Koncert''), sp\u00e4ter auch im [[Gewandhaus Leipzig]] mit. \n-->\nHis most important work is a great choirbook from 1819. Besides that, he wrote masses, motets, cantatas, a setting of the 100th Psalm, four Te deums, one piano concerto, sonatas and capriccio.\n\nHe is believed to have been the editor of the first edition of [[Motet (Bach)|Bach's motets]].<ref>[https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Lib/Schicht-Johann-Gottfried.htm Johann Gottfried Schicht (Composer, Thomaskantor)] Bach Cantatas Website</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMSLP|id=Schicht, Johann Gottfried}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|117226157|TYP=Werke von und \u00fcber}}\n\n{{Gewandhausorchester conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schicht, Johann Gottfried}}\n[[Category:1753 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bogatynia]]\n[[Category:People from the Electorate of Saxony]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Thomaskantors]]\n\n\n{{germany-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the German composer and conductor|the German-Czech entrepreneur|Johann Schicht}}\n{{more references|date=February 2010}}\n[[File:Johann Gottfried Schicht.jpg|250px|thumb|Johann Gottfried Schicht]]\n'''Johann Gottfried Schicht''' (29 September 1753 &ndash; 16 February 1823) was a [[Germany|German]] [[composer]] and [[Conducting|conductor]].\n\nSchicht was born in [[Bogatynia|Reichenau]], in the [[Electorate of Saxony]]. He trained as a lawyer, studying from 1776 at Leipzig. He was the conductor of the [[Leipzig Gewandhaus Orchestra]] from 1785 to 1810, when he was succeeded by [[Johann Philipp Christian Schulz]]. Schicht continued to work in Leipzig, serving as [[Thomaskantor]], director of the [[Thomanerchor]] with reponsibility for music in the city's churches. He was in post from 1810 until 1823, when he died, aged 69, in Leipzig.\n\n<!-- Schicht wirkte als [[Akkompagnist]] und [[Violinist]] an den von [[Johann Adam Hiller]] veranstalteten Konzerten (''Gro\u00dfes Koncert''), sp\u00e4ter auch im [[Gewandhaus Leipzig]] mit. \n-->\nHis most important work is a great choirbook from 1819. Besides that, he wrote masses, motets, cantatas, a setting of the 100th Psalm, four Te deums, one piano concerto, sonatas and capriccio.\n\nHe is believed to have been the editor of the first edition of [[Motet (Bach)|Bach's motets]].<ref>[https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Lib/Schicht-Johann-Gottfried.htm Johann Gottfried Schicht (Composer, Thomaskantor)] Bach Cantatas Website</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMSLP|id=Schicht, Johann Gottfried}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|117226157|TYP=Werke von und \u00fcber}}\n\n{{Gewandhausorchester conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schicht, Johann Gottfried}}\n[[Category:1753 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bogatynia]]\n[[Category:People from the Electorate of Saxony]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Thomaskantors]]\n\n\n{{germany-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Gottfried_Schicht"}
{"title_page": "Balls Pond Road Cemetery", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date= March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Balls Pond Road Cemetery (Kingsbury Road Cemetery)\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1843\n| country     = England\n| location    = Kingsbury Road, [[Dalston]] ([[London Borough of Islington]])\n| type        = Jewish\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[West London Synagogue]]\n| size        = 0.5 acres\n| graves      = 900\n| interments  = \n| website     = \n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2284789/kingsbury-road-cemetery Kingsbury Road Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n'''Balls Pond Road Cemetery''', also known as '''Jewish (West London Reform) Cemetery,'''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/> '''Kingsbury Road Cemetery''', '''Balls Pond Burial Ground'''<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.apex.net.au/~tmj/balls-pond/ |title=Balls Pond Burial Ground |last=Martin-Jones |first=Tony |date=25 November 2015 |website=www.apex.net.au |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and '''The Jewish Burial Ground''',<ref name = \"Gardens\"/> is  a  Jewish cemetery on Kingsbury Road, [[W postcode area |London W1]]. It was founded in 1843 and is owned by [[West London Synagogue]].<ref name = \"Meller216\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 216|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref> The last burial was in 1951.<ref name = \"Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=ISL041 |title= The Jewish Burial Ground |website=[[London Gardens Online]] |publisher=[[London Parks and Gardens Trust]] |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Prominent early members of the West London Synagogue, such as the de Stern, [[Goldsmid family|Goldsmid]] and [[Mocatta]] families, are buried in this cemetery.<ref name=\"Parks & Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/the-jewish-burial-ground-islington |title=The Jewish Burial Ground, Islington |website=Parks & Gardens |publisher=Hestercombe Gardens Trust |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n[[File:David Woolf Marks.jpg|120px| thumb|Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]]]] \nPeople buried at the cemetery include:\n* Sir [[Isaac Lyon Goldsmid]], 1st Baronet (1778\u20131859), financier and one of the leading figures in the Jewish emancipation in the United Kingdom<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*Sir [[Julian Goldsmid]], 3rd Baronet (1838\u20131896), lawyer, businessman, Liberal (later Liberal Unionist) MP, [[List of vice-chancellors of the University of London|Vice-Chancellor of the University of London]] and art collector<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[Amy Levy]] (1861\u20131889), essayist, poet, and novelist, who was the first Jewish woman at [[Cambridge University]] and the first Jewish woman to be cremated in England; her ashes were interred at this cemetery<ref name=\"Medd\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=28rZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=west+london+synagogue+balls+pond+road&source=bl&ots=CPH-nv0Jtv&sig=ACfU3U20fguC4hulqjaD2WJcxC2r1J4pqQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6qvGevcXoAhWPN8AKHRejCQs4ChDoATAIegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=west%20london%20synagogue%20balls%20pond%20road&f=false|title=The Cambridge Companion to Lesbian Literature |date=2015 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |editor-last=Medd |editor-first=Jodie |pages=127|ISBN= 978-1-107-05400-4}}</ref>\n*[[Joseph Moses Levy]] (1812\u20131888), newspaper editor and publisher, who was chief proprietor of  ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' and also managed ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[James Joseph Sylvester]] (1814\u20131897), mathematician and [[University of Oxford]] professor. Sylvester made fundamental contributions to [[matrix theory]], [[invariant theory]], [[number theory]], [[partition theory]] and [[combinatorics]]. He played a leadership role in American mathematics in the later half of the 19th century as a professor at the [[Johns Hopkins University]] and as founder of the ''[[American Journal of Mathematics]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0-902-198-84-X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"UCL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/economics/about-department/famous-economists/james-joseph-sylvester-1814-1897 |title=James Joseph Sylvester (1814\u20131897) |publisher=[[University College London]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]] (1811\u20131909), Hebrew scholar and minister, who was the first religious leader of the West London Synagogue<ref name=\"Marks\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I9088&tree=Cemeteries | title=MARKS Rev. Prof David Woolf [David b Benjamin Ze'ev] 1811\u20131909 | publisher=Cemetery Scribes | date=22 August 2009 | accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n*[[David Mocatta]] (1806\u20131882), architect of railway stations and synagogues, and a founder of the West London Synagogue<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|London}}\n\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judaism in London]]\n[[Category:Religion in the London Borough of Islington]]\n\n{{UK-cemetery-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cemetery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date= March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Balls Pond Road Cemetery (Kingsbury Road Cemetery)\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1843\n| country     = England\n| location    = Kingsbury Road, [[Dalston]] ([[London Borough of Islington]])\n| type        = Jewish\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[West London Synagogue]]\n| size        = 0.5 acres\n| graves      = 900\n| interments  = \n| website     = \n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2284789/kingsbury-road-cemetery Kingsbury Road Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n'''Balls Pond Road Cemetery''', also known as '''Jewish (West London Reform) Cemetery,'''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/> '''Kingsbury Road Cemetery''', '''Balls Pond Burial Ground'''<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.apex.net.au/~tmj/balls-pond/ |title=Balls Pond Burial Ground |last=Martin-Jones |first=Tony |date=25 November 2015 |website=www.apex.net.au |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and '''The Jewish Burial Ground''',<ref name = \"Gardens\"/> is  a  Jewish cemetery on Kingsbury Road, [[W postcode area |London W1]]. It was founded in 1843 and is owned by [[West London Synagogue]].<ref name = \"Meller216\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 216|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref> The last burial was in 1951.<ref name = \"Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=ISL041 |title= The Jewish Burial Ground |website=[[London Gardens Online]] |publisher=[[London Parks and Gardens Trust]] |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Prominent early members of the West London Synagogue, such as the de Stern, [[Goldsmid family|Goldsmid]] and [[Mocatta]] families, are buried in this cemetery.<ref name=\"Parks & Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/the-jewish-burial-ground-islington |title=The Jewish Burial Ground, Islington |website=Parks & Gardens |publisher=Hestercombe Gardens Trust |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n[[File:David Woolf Marks.jpg|120px| thumb|Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]]]] \nPeople buried at the cemetery include:\n* Sir [[Isaac Lyon Goldsmid]], 1st Baronet (1778\u20131859), financier and one of the leading figures in the Jewish emancipation in the United Kingdom<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*Sir [[Julian Goldsmid]], 3rd Baronet (1838\u20131896), lawyer, businessman, Liberal (later Liberal Unionist) MP, [[List of vice-chancellors of the University of London|Vice-Chancellor of the University of London]] and art collector<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[Amy Levy]] (1861\u20131889), essayist, poet, and novelist, who was the first Jewish woman at [[Cambridge University]] and the first Jewish woman to be cremated in England; her ashes were interred at this cemetery<ref name=\"Medd\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=28rZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=west+london+synagogue+balls+pond+road&source=bl&ots=CPH-nv0Jtv&sig=ACfU3U20fguC4hulqjaD2WJcxC2r1J4pqQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6qvGevcXoAhWPN8AKHRejCQs4ChDoATAIegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=west%20london%20synagogue%20balls%20pond%20road&f=false|title=The Cambridge Companion to Lesbian Literature |date=2015 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |editor-last=Medd |editor-first=Jodie |pages=127|ISBN= 978-1-107-05400-4}}</ref>\n*[[Joseph Moses Levy]] (1812\u20131888), newspaper editor and publisher, who was chief proprietor of  ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' and also managed ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[James Joseph Sylvester]] (1814\u20131897), mathematician and [[University of Oxford]] professor. He made fundamental contributions to [[matrix theory]], [[invariant theory]], [[number theory]], [[partition theory]] and [[combinatorics]]. He played a leadership role in American mathematics in the later half of the 19th century as a professor at the [[Johns Hopkins University]] and as founder of the ''[[American Journal of Mathematics]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0-902-198-84-X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"UCL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/economics/about-department/famous-economists/james-joseph-sylvester-1814-1897 |title=James Joseph Sylvester (1814\u20131897) |publisher=[[University College London]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]] (1811\u20131909), Hebrew scholar and minister, who was the first religious leader of the West London Synagogue<ref name=\"Marks\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I9088&tree=Cemeteries | title=MARKS Rev. Prof David Woolf [David b Benjamin Ze'ev] 1811\u20131909 | publisher=Cemetery Scribes | date=22 August 2009 | accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n*[[David Mocatta]] (1806\u20131882), architect of railway stations and synagogues, and a founder of the West London Synagogue<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|London}}\n\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judaism in London]]\n[[Category:Religion in the London Borough of Islington]]\n\n{{UK-cemetery-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cemetery-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable burials:Copyedit (minor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balls_Pond_Road_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Taihoku Air Strike", "text_new": "The '''Taihoku Air Strike''' was an [[strategic bombing|air raid]] by the military of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] against the metropolitan perimeter of Taihoku (modern-day [[Taipei]]), the capital of [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese Taiwan]], during January 1938. The raid was the first attack on [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] territory during the course of World War II, and one of the few offensive operations conducted by China directly against Japan during the course of the war.\n\n==Operation==\nThe Taihoku Air Strike Operation was conducted by the [[Republic of China Air Force]], using a squadron of nine [[Martin 139]] bombers. The aircraft were deployed from an airfield in either [[Chekiang]] or [[Fujian|Fukien]] province, and flew uncontested over the [[Taiwan Strait]]. Once over metropolitan Taihoku, the aircraft dropped leaflets, or according to some sources made a minor bombing strike, and successfully returned to the mainland, under Japanese [[antiaircraft]] fire. Contemporary newspaper accounts stated that eight people were killed and 25 were wounded.<ref>[http://www.newspaperarchive.com/LandingPage.aspx?type=glp&search=taihoku%20air%20raid&img=\\\\na0038\\6838621\\93461159_clean.html] Daily Capital News.  February 24, 1938.</ref>\n\nWhile achieving little militarily, this represented the first instance of an air raid over Japanese territory, preceding the [[Doolittle raid]] against [[Tokyo]] by four years.\n\nOne foreign eyewitness, [[United States|American]] diplomat [[George H. Kerr]], described the air raid to the foreign press, and mentioned that as a result, sand barricades were built around important government and commerce buildings, anti-aircraft guns were deployed, and internal security strengthened against possible [[fifth column]] activity by the local ethnic Chinese population.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taihoku Air Raid]]\n*[[Development of Chinese Nationalist air force (1937\u201345)]]\n\n[[Category:Second Sino-Japanese War]]\n[[Category:1938 in China]]\n[[Category:1938 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Taiwan under Japanese rule]]\n[[Category:1938 in Taiwan]]\n\n\n{{China-hist-stub}}\n{{Japan-battle-stub}}\n{{mil-aviation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Taihoku Air Strike''' was an [[strategic bombing|air raid]] by the military of the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] against the metropolitan perimeter of Taihoku (modern-day [[Taipei]]), the capital of [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese Taiwan]], during January 1938. The raid was the first attack on [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] territory during the course of World War II, and one of the few offensive operations conducted by China directly against Japan during the course of the war.\n\n==Operation==\nThe Taihoku Air Strike Operation was conducted by the [[Republic of China Air Force]], using a squadron of nine [[Martin 139]] bombers. The aircraft were deployed from an airfield in either [[Chekiang]] or [[Fujian|Fukien]] province, and flew uncontested over the [[Taiwan Strait]]. Once over metropolitan Taihoku, the aircraft dropped leaflets, or according to some sources made a minor bombing strike, and successfully returned to the mainland, under Japanese [[antiaircraft]] fire. Contemporary newspaper accounts stated that eight people were killed and 25 were wounded.<ref>[http://www.newspaperarchive.com/LandingPage.aspx?type=glp&search=taihoku%20air%20raid&img=\\\\na0038\\6838621\\93461159_clean.html] Daily Capital News.  February 24, 1938</ref>\n\nWhile achieving little militarily, this represented the first instance of an air raid over Japanese territory, preceding the [[Doolittle raid]] against [[Tokyo]] by four years.\n\nOne foreign eyewitness, [[United States|American]] diplomat [[George H. Kerr]], described the air raid to the foreign press, and mentioned that as a result, sand barricades were built around important government and commerce buildings, anti-aircraft guns were deployed, and internal security strengthened against possible [[fifth column]] activity by the local ethnic Chinese population.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Taihoku Air Raid]]\n*[[Development of Chinese Nationalist air force (1937\u201345)]]\n\n[[Category:Second Sino-Japanese War]]\n[[Category:1938 in China]]\n[[Category:1938 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Taiwan under Japanese rule]]\n[[Category:1938 in Taiwan]]\n\n\n{{China-hist-stub}}\n{{Japan-battle-stub}}\n{{mil-aviation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Derim Hunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOperation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taihoku_Air_Strike"}
